{"title_page": "Iraqi Kurdish Civil War", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Iraqi Kurdish Civil War\n|partof=the [[Iraqi\u2013Kurdish conflict]] and the [[Iraqi no-fly zones]] conflict\n|image= \n|caption=\n|date=May 1994 \u2013 24 November 1997\n|place=[[Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n|result=Washington Agreement, [[ceasefire]]; creation of two Kurdish regional governments, one in [[Sulaymaniyah]] and one in [[Erbil]]\n* [[Kurdistan Workers' Party|PKK]] moved to [[Qandil mountains]] from [[Bekaa Valley]]\n|combatant1 ={{flagicon image|Former Flag of KDP.png}} [[Kurdistan Democratic Party|KDP]]<br />\n{{flagicon|Iraq|1991}} [[Ba'athist Iraq|Iraq]]<br />\n{{flag|Turkey}}<br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag of KDP-I.png}} [[Kurdish Democratic Party of Iran|PDKI]]<br>'''Support'''<br>{{flag|Belarus}}<ref>[https://news.tut.by/society/14066.html \u041f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043b\u044f\u044e\u0442 \u043b\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0438 \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044c \u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0435 \u0418\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0443?]</ref>{{Dubious |Belarus listed as supporter|reason=Listed source only indicates a commercial arms trade relationship, which does not appear to be connected to this offensive in perticular. Furthermore, Belarus is singled out as a supporter, despite several other countries also being listed as engaging in commercial arms trade with Iraq during this period.|date=September 2019}}\n\n|combatant2 ={{flagicon image|Flag of PUK.png}} [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan|PUK]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|PKK flag 1978.svg}} [[Kurdistan Workers Party|PKK]]<br />\n[[Kurdistan Conservative Party|KCP]]<br />\n[[Iraqi National Congress]]<br />\n{{flag|Iran}} (from 1995)<br />\n{{flagicon image|ISCI flag.svg}} [[SCIRI]]\n|commander1={{flagicon image|Former Flag of KDP.png}} [[Massoud Barzani]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|Former Flag of KDP.png}} [[Rowsch Shaways]]<br />\n{{flagicon|Iraq|1991}} [[Saddam Hussein]]<br />\n{{flagicon|Turkey}} [[\u0130smail Hakk\u0131 Karaday\u0131]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag of KDP-I.png}} [[Mustafa Hijri]]\n|commander2={{flagicon image|Flag of PUK.png}} [[Jalal Talabani]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag of PUK.png}} [[Nawshirwan Mustafa]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag of PUK.png}} [[Kosrat Rasul Ali]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag of Kurdistan Workers' Party 1978.svg}} [[Abdullah \u00d6calan]]\n[[Ahmed Chalabi]]\n|strength1={{flagicon image|Former Flag of KDP.png}} KDP: 25,000 active, 30,000 reserves<ref name=\"fsu\">[http://etd.lib.fsu.edu/theses/available/etd-11142005-144616/unrestricted/003Manuscript.pdf Willing to face Death: A History of Kurdish Military Forces - the Peshmerga - from the Ottoman Empire to Present-Day Iraq (page 63)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029191132/http://etd.lib.fsu.edu/theses/available/etd-11142005-144616/unrestricted/003Manuscript.pdf |date=29 October 2013 }}, Michael G. Lortz</ref><br />\n{{flagicon|Iraq|1991}} Iraq: 30,000 (1996)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.countriesquest.com/middle_east/iraq/history/persian_gulf_war_and_aftermath.htm |title=Persian Gulf War and Aftermath - History - Iraq - Middle East: embargo iraq, crisis iraq, power united, exchange rate, end year |publisher=Countriesquest.com |date=15 January 1991 |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref><br />\n{{flag|Turkey}}: 50,000 (1997)<ref name=\"KDP\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gP_-8rXzQs8C&pg=PA4227|title=The Europa World Year: Kazakhstan - Zimbabwe|publisher=|accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag of KDP-I.png}} PDKI: 600 (1998)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,74703,00.html|title=Iraqi Insurgent Groups|work=Fox News|accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n|strength2={{flagicon image|Flag of PUK.png}} PUK: 12,000 active, 6,000 reserves<ref name=\"fsu\"/><br />INC: 1,000 (1995)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historycommons.org/timeline.jsp?specific_cases_and_issues=chalabi&timeline=complete_timeline_of_the_2003_invasion_of_iraq|title=Events Leading Up to the 2003 Invasion of Iraq|publisher=|accessdate=1 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116052701/http://www.historycommons.org/timeline.jsp?specific_cases_and_issues=chalabi&timeline=complete_timeline_of_the_2003_invasion_of_iraq|archive-date=16 November 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag of Kurdistan Workers' Party 1978.svg}} PKK: 5,000\u201310,000 (1994)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/war/kurdistan-turkey-insurrection.htm|title=Kurdistan - Turkey|author=John Pike|publisher=|accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><br />\n{{flag|Iran}}: 2,000 (1996)<ref>[http://www.irainc.org/pub/NIreport.pdf Unsafe Haven: Iranian Kurdish Refugees in Iraqi Kurdistan (page 1)]</ref><br />\n{{flagicon image|Badr Organisation Military flag.svg}} [[SCIRI]]: 5,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meforum.org/384/turkey-and-iran-face-off-in-kurdistan |title=Turkey and Iran Face off in Kurdistan :: Middle East Quarterly |publisher=Meforum.org |date= |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref>\n|casualties1=\n|casualties2=\n|casualties3= unknown and do not touch this again <ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Middle_East/LB20Ak02.html |title=Asia Times Online :: Middle East News, Iraq, Iran current affairs |publisher=Atimes.com |date=20 February 2010 |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Iraqi Kurdish Civil War}}\n{{Campaignbox Kurdish\u2013Iraqi conflict}}\n{{Campaignbox Kurdish\u2013Turkish conflict}}\n\nThe '''Iraqi Kurdish Civil War''' was a military conflict that took place between rival [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]] factions in [[Iraqi Kurdistan]] during the mid-1990s, mostly between the [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]] and the [[Kurdistan Democratic Party]]. Over the course of the conflict, Kurdish factions from [[Iranian Kurdistan|Iranian]] and [[Turkish Kurdistan]], as well as Iranian, Iraqi and Turkish state forces, were drawn into the fighting, with additional involvement from American forces. Between 3,000 and 5,000 fighters and civilians were killed.\n\n==Background==\nAutonomy in [[Iraqi Kurdistan]] was originally established in 1970 as the ''Kurdish Autonomous Region'' following the agreement of an Autonomy Accord between the government of Iraq and leaders of the Iraqi [[Kurds|Kurdish]] community. A Legislative Assembly was established in the city of Erbil with nominal authority over the Kurdish-populated governorates of [[Erbil Governorate|Erbil]], [[Dohuk Governorate|Dahuk]] and [[As Sulaymaniyah Governorate|As Sulaymaniyah]]. As various battles between separatist Kurds and Iraqi government forces continued until the [[1991 uprisings in Iraq]], the safety of Kurdish refugees led to the adoption of [[United Nations Security Council]] [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 688|Resolution 688]] which was used as a justification to implement [[Operation Provide Comfort]], a US-led multinational military operation that ensured the security of the Iraqi Kurdish region through the use of air power while simultaneously providing humanitarian aid to refugees fleeing persecution.<ref>L. Fawcett, ''Down but not out? The Kurds in International Politics'', Reviews of International Studies, Vol.27, 2001 p.117</ref> While the no-fly zone covered Dahuk and Erbil, it left out Sulaymaniyah and [[Kirkuk]]. This led to a further series of bloody clashes between Iraqi government forces and Kurdish troops. Shortly thereafter, an uneasy balance of power was reached, and Iraq withdrew its military and government officials from the region in October 1991. From that point on, Iraqi Kurdistan had achieved ''de facto'' independence under the leadership of the region's two principal Kurdish parties \u2013 the [[Kurdistan Democratic Party of Iraq|Kurdish Democratic Party]] and the [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]] \u2013 free from the control of [[Baghdad]]. The region then adopted its own flag and national anthem.\n\nIraqi Kurdistan held [[1992 Iraqi Kurdistan parliamentary election|parliamentary elections]] in 1992. The KDP gained an absolute majority of the votes in the [[Governorates of Iraq|governorates]] of [[Dohuk Governorate|Dohuk]] and [[Arbil Province|Arbil]], whereas the PUK garnered the broad support of the [[Sulaymaniyah Governorate|Sulaymaniyah]] governorate as well as the Kurdish portions of [[Diyala Governorate|Diyala]] (specifically the [[Kifri District|Kifri]] and [[Khanaqin District]]s). As a result of the election, the Kurdish parliament was split between [[Jalal Talabani]]'s Patriotic Union of Kurdistan and [[Massoud Barzani]]'s Kurdish Democratic Party.<ref name=\"slate.com\">{{cite web|last=Politi |first=Daniel |url=http://www.slate.com/id/1032/ |title=The Kurds - Slate Magazine |publisher=Slate.com |date= |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter withdrawing its forces from Kurdistan in October 1991, the Iraqi government imposed an economic blockade over the region, restricting its oil and food supplies.<ref>M. Leezenberg, ''Iraqi Kurdistan: contours of a post-civil war society'', Third World Quarterly, Vol.26, No.4-5, June 2005, p.636</ref> The United Nations embargo on Iraq also significantly affected the Kurdish economy, preventing trade between the Kurds and other nations. As such, all economic dealings between Iraqi Kurdistan and the outside world were done through the [[black market]].\n\nIn March 1994 [[Turkish Armed Forces]] began [[Operation Steel]], a cross-border military incursion into [[Iraqi Kurdistan|northern Iraq]] against the [[Kurdistan Workers' Party|PKK]]. On May 3 a delegation from the KDP agreed to not allow the PKK to have a base in northern Iraq. On May 4, Turkish Armed Forces left northern Iraq.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kurds in Turkey |url=http://www.asylumlaw.org/docs/turkey/mar99_turkey_kurds.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716081035/http://www.asylumlaw.org/docs/turkey/mar99_turkey_kurds.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=16 July 2011 |website=Asylum Law |accessdate=19 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==1994 PUK\u2013KDP clashes==\n{{main|May 1994 PUK\u2013KDP clashes}}\n\nFighting broke out between the two factions in May 1994. The initial clashes left around 300 people dead, <ref name=\"globalsecurity.org\">{{cite web|author=John Pike |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/kdp.htm |title=Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) |publisher=Globalsecurity.org |date= |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref> and over the next year, around 2,000 people were killed on both sides.<ref name=\"slate.com\"/> According to former CIA officer [[Robert Baer]], members of the Iranian [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] provided limited support to the PUK and allowed the PUK to launch attacks from Iranian territory.\n\n==Planned assassination of Saddam Hussein==\nIn January 1995, [[CIA]] case officer [[Robert Baer]] traveled to northern Iraq with a five-man team to set up a CIA station. He made contact with the Kurdish leadership and managed to negotiate a truce between Barzani and Talabani.\n\nWithin days, Baer made contact with an Iraqi general who was plotting to assassinate [[Saddam Hussein]]. The plan was to use a unit of 100 renegade Iraqi troops to kill Saddam as he passed over a bridge near [[Tikrit]]. Baer cabled the plan to Washington but did not hear anything back. After three weeks, the plan was revised, calling for an attack by Kurdish forces in northern Iraq while rebel Iraqi troops leveled one of Saddam's houses with tank fire in order to kill the Iraqi leader. Baer again cabled the plan to Washington and received no response. On 28 February, the [[Iraqi Army]] was placed on full alert. In response, the Iranian and Turkish militaries were also placed on high alert. Baer received a message directly from National Security Advisor [[Tony Lake]] telling him his operation was compromised. This warning was passed on Baer's Kurdish and Iraqi contacts. Upon learning this, Barzani backed out of the planned offensive, leaving Talabani's PUK forces to carry it out alone.\n\nThe Iraqi Army officers planning to kill Saddam with tank fire were compromised, arrested and executed before they could carry out the operation. The PUK's offensive was still launched as planned, and within days they managed to destroy three Iraqi Army divisions and capture 5,000 prisoners.<ref name=\"wmassociation.com\">[http://www.wmassociation.com/reports/spkers/baer.html Robert Baer speech at World Media Association]  {{webarchive |url=https://archive.today/20070816094817/http://www.wmassociation.com/reports/spkers/baer.html |date=16 August 2007 }}</ref> Despite Baer's pleas for American support of the offensive, none was forthcoming, and the Kurdish troops were forced to withdraw. Baer was immediately recalled from Iraq, briefly investigated for the attempted murder of Saddam Hussein, but exonerated.<ref name=\"wmassociation.com\"/>\n\n==Battle of Erbil (1996)==\n{{main|Battle of Erbil (1996)}}\nAlthough the Kurdish parliament ceased to meet in May 1996, the fragile cease-fire between the PUK and KDP held until the summer of 1996. During this period, the Iraqi government was permitted by the KDP to establish a smuggling route through the [[Khabur (Euphrates)|Khabur River]] basin for the transportation of illegal petroleum exports.<ref name=\"TTS1\">{{cite book|last1=Pollack|first1=Kenneth|title=The Threatening Storm: What Every American Needs to Know Before an Invasion in Iraq|date=25 March 2003|publisher=Random House LLC, 2003|isbn=9781588363411|page=81|edition=The Case for Invading Iraq: An Excerpt from The Threatening Storm|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HCZfUV-U97kC&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&source=bl&ots=6vPivVVOt_&sig=hX-9bcgfdd2M-aiaCt2IjW0HmxU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=WR2qU9L2L4OYyASTyILgDA&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=25 June 2014}}</ref> Barzani and his associates seized the opportunity to impose taxation on this trade, giving them an income of several million dollars per week.<ref>{{cite book |last=Stansfield |first=G. |last2=Anderson |first2=L. |title=The Future of Iraq: Dictatorship, Democracy, or Division? |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |location=New York |year=2004 |page=174 |isbn=1403963541}}</ref> This led to a dispute with the PUK over who should benefit from this money. Although the two parties reached an agreement where the Iraqi\u2013Turkish smuggling routes would be divided evenly between them, the KDP continued its attempts to exert greater control over the movement of goods through Iraqi Kurdistan.<ref name=TTS1 />\n\nTalabani established an alliance with Iran, permitting it to conduct a military incursion into northern Iraq aimed at the [[Kurdish Democratic Party of Iran]] on 28 July.<ref name=\"slate.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=John Pike |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/kdpi.htm |title=Kurdish Democratic Party of Iran (KDPI) |publisher=Globalsecurity.org |date= |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref> In response, Barzani asked for assistance from the Iraqi government who, seeing an opportunity to retake northern Iraq, accepted. On 31 August, 30,000 Iraqi troops, spearheaded by an armored division of the [[Iraqi Republican Guard]], attacked the PUK-held city of [[Erbil]], which was defended by 3,000 PUK Peshmerga led by Korsat Rasul Ali, in conjunction with KDP forces. Erbil was captured, and Iraqi troops executed 700 PUK and [[Iraqi National Congress]] [[prisoners of war]] in a field outside the city.\n\nThis attack stoked Kurdish fears that Saddam intended to launch a genocidal campaign against the Kurds similar to the campaigns of [[Al-Anfal Campaign|1988]] and [[1991 uprisings in Iraq|1991]]. The Clinton administration, unwilling to allow the Iraqi government to regain control of Iraqi Kurdistan, began [[Operation Desert Strike]] on 3 September, when American ships and [[B-52 Stratofortress]] bombers launched 27 cruise missiles at air defense sites in southern Iraq. The next day, 17 more cruise missiles were launched from American ships against Iraqi air defense sites. The United States also deployed strike aircraft and an aircraft carrier to the [[Persian Gulf]] region, and the extent of the southern no-fly zone was moved northwards to the [[33rd parallel north|33rd parallel]].<ref>{{cite web|author=John Pike |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/ops/desert_strike.htm |title=Operation Desert Strike |publisher=Globalsecurity.org |date= |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter installing the KDP in control of Erbil, [[Iraqi Army]] troops withdrew from the Kurdish region back to their initial positions. The KDP drove the PUK from its other strongholds, and with additional Iraqi Army help, captured Sulaymaniyah on 9 September. Jalal Talabani and the PUK retreated to the Iranian border, and American forces evacuated 700 Iraqi National Congress personnel and 6,000 PUK members out of northern Iraq.<ref name=\"slate.com\"/><ref name=\"globalsecurity.org\"/> On 13 October, Sulaymaniyah was recaptured by the PUK, allegedly with support of Iranian forces.<ref name=\"UNHCR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/country,,MARP,,IRQ,,469f38a6c,0.html|title=Refworld - Chronology for Kurds in Iraq|author=United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|work=Refworld|accessdate=1 May 2016|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017070825/http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/country%2C%2CMARP%2C%2CIRQ%2C%2C469f38a6c%2C0.html|archivedate=17 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Turkish intervention==\n{{main|Operation Hammer (1997)|Operation Dawn (1997)}}\n\nFighting continued throughout the winter between the KDP and PUK. Complicating matters, PKK was present in Iraq. PKK was allied with the PUK which later led KDP attack the PKK. According to some sources, the PKK began to fight against all who supported KDP, including some Assyrian and Arab groups.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|author=John Pike |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/puk.htm |title=Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) |publisher=Globalsecurity.org |date= |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref> Turkey which saw the Kurdish Civil war as an opportunity, allied with KDP and launched [[Operation Hammer (1997)|Operation Hammer]] in May, in a violent attempt to force the PKK to leave Iraqi Kurdistan. This operation caused heavy PKK casualties but was unsuccessful. PKK succeeded to keep their camps in Northern Iraq.<ref>{{cite book|title=The State of the Middle East: An Atlas of Conflict and Resolution|page=92|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MehRAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA92&lpg=PA92&dq=KDP+attacked+PKK+1994&source=bl&ots=4LYoA6JpQH&sig=jfnfDJT2P7NXlpZck0ZvXK0b_58&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjYiIWqrpfLAhXDJJoKHbJXDy4Q6AEIKzAE#v=onepage&q=KDP%20attacked%20PKK%201994&f=false|accessdate=27 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September 1997, Turkish forces re-entered Iraqi Kurdistan and attacked PUK and PKK positions in an attempt to force the PKK to leave Iraqi Kurdistan. However, according to Turkish sources, it was an attempt to bring a cease-fire between the factions. The operation resulted in heavy PKK and PUK casualties. Later a cease-fire was negotiated between the PUK and KDP after the US decision to support a cease-fire.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nDespite the cease-fire, renewed fighting broke out along the armistice line between the KDP and PUK in October and November. In this round of fighting, 1,200 combatants were killed on both sides and 10,000 civilians fled their homes.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> On 24 November 1997, the KDP declared a unilateral cease-fire. The PUK, although not declaring a cease-fire officially, said their group would respect the truce, despite alleging that the KDP had violated the truce by attacking PUK positions on 25 November.<ref name=\"UNHCR\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Iraq kurdish areas 2003 vector.svg|300px|thumb|Division of Kurdistan after the civil war]]\n\nIn September 1998, [[Massoud Barzani|Barzani]] and [[Jalal Talabani|Talabani]] signed the U.S.-mediated Washington Agreement establishing a formal peace treaty. In the agreement, the parties agreed to share revenue, share power, deny the use of northern Iraq to the [[Kurdistan Workers' Party|PKK]], and not allow Iraqi troops into the Kurdish regions. The United States pledged to use military force to protect the Kurds from possible aggression by [[Saddam Hussein]]. At the same time, implementation of the U.N. [[Oil-for-Food Programme]] brought revenue to northern Iraq, allowing for increased standards of living.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewashingtoninstitute.org/templateC05.php?CID=1219 |title=Kurdish Agreement Signals New U.S. Commitment |publisher=The Washington Institute for Near East Policy |date=29 September 1998 |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref> Iraqi Kurdistan became a relatively peaceful region, before the small terrorist group [[Ansar al-Islam]] entered the Halabja region in December 2001, bringing renewed conflict that would end in 2003 immediately prior to start of Iraq war, which mainly affected non-Kurdish areas of Iraq.\n\nAround a month later, U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]] signed the [[Iraq Liberation Act]] into law, providing for military assistance to Iraqi opposition groups, including the PUK and KDP. The KDP estimated that 58,000 of its supporters had been expelled from PUK-controlled regions from October 1996 to October 1997. The PUK says 49,000 of its supporters were expelled from KDP-controlled regions from August 1996 to December 1997.<ref name=\"globalsecurity.org\" />\n\nThe PUK and KDP later co-operated with American forces during the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], routing Iraqi forces with the help of American air power and overrunning much of northern Iraq including the cities of [[Kirkuk]] and [[Mosul]]. After the invasion, Massoud Barzani was later elected president of Iraqi Kurdistan while Jalal Talabani was elected [[President of Iraq]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of wars involving Iraq]]\n* [[List of wars involving Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n* [[List of modern conflicts in the Middle East]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* [https://www.jstor.org/stable/pdf/4328927.pdf?seq=1 The KDP-PUK Conflict in Northern Iraq]\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Cite book|isbn=140004684X|title=See No Evil: The True Story of a Ground Soldier in the CIA's War on Terrorism |last=Baer |first=Robert |publisher=Three Rivers Press|year=2003}}\n* {{Cite book|isbn=0375509283|title=The Threatening Storm: The Case for Invading Iraq|last=Pollack|first=Kenneth|publisher=Random House|year=2002|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/threateningstorm00poll}}\n\n{{Post-Cold War Asian conflicts}}\n\n[[Category:Iraqi\u2013Kurdish conflict]]\n[[Category:1994 in Iraq]]\n[[Category:1995 in Iraq]]\n[[Category:1996 in Iraq]]\n[[Category:1997 in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1994]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1995]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1996]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1997]]\n[[Category:Civil wars in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Civil wars post-1945]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Iran]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Iraq]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Kurdistan Region (Iraq)]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the United States]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Turkey]]\n[[Category:1990s in Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Iraqi Kurdish Civil War\n|partof=the [[Iraqi\u2013Kurdish conflict]] and the [[Iraqi no-fly zones]] conflict\n|image= \n|caption=\n|date=May 1994 \u2013 24 November 1997\n|place=[[Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n|result=Washington Agreement, [[ceasefire]]; creation of two Kurdish regional governments, one in [[Sulaymaniyah]] and one in [[Erbil]]\n* [[Kurdistan Workers' Party|PKK]] moved to [[Qandil mountains]] from [[Bekaa Valley]]\n|combatant1 ={{flagicon image|Former Flag of KDP.png}} [[Kurdistan Democratic Party|KDP]]<br />\n{{flagicon|Iraq|1991}} [[Ba'athist Iraq|Iraq]]<br />\n{{flag|Turkey}}<br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag of KDP-I.png}} [[Kurdish Democratic Party of Iran|PDKI]]<br>'''Support'''<br>{{flag|Belarus}}<ref>[https://news.tut.by/society/14066.html \u041f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043b\u044f\u044e\u0442 \u043b\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0438 \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044c \u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0435 \u0418\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0443?]</ref>{{Dubious |Belarus listed as supporter|reason=Listed source only indicates a commercial arms trade relationship, which does not appear to be connected to this offensive in perticular. Furthermore, Belarus is singled out as a supporter, despite several other countries also being listed as engaging in commercial arms trade with Iraq during this period.|date=September 2019}}\n\n|combatant2 ={{flagicon image|Flag of PUK.png}} [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan|PUK]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|PKK flag 1978.svg}} [[Kurdistan Workers Party|PKK]]<br />\n[[Kurdistan Conservative Party|KCP]]<br />\n[[Iraqi National Congress]]<br />\n{{flag|Iran}} (from 1995)<br />\n{{flagicon image|ISCI flag.svg}} [[SCIRI]]\n|commander1={{flagicon image|Former Flag of KDP.png}} [[Massoud Barzani]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|Former Flag of KDP.png}} [[Rowsch Shaways]]<br />\n{{flagicon|Iraq|1991}} [[Saddam Hussein]]<br />\n{{flagicon|Turkey}} [[\u0130smail Hakk\u0131 Karaday\u0131]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag of KDP-I.png}} [[Mustafa Hijri]]\n|commander2={{flagicon image|Flag of PUK.png}} [[Jalal Talabani]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag of PUK.png}} [[Nawshirwan Mustafa]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag of PUK.png}} [[Kosrat Rasul Ali]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag of Kurdistan Workers' Party 1978.svg}} [[Abdullah \u00d6calan]]\n[[Ahmed Chalabi]]\n|strength1={{flagicon image|Former Flag of KDP.png}} KDP: 25,000 active, 30,000 reserves<ref name=\"fsu\">[http://etd.lib.fsu.edu/theses/available/etd-11142005-144616/unrestricted/003Manuscript.pdf Willing to face Death: A History of Kurdish Military Forces - the Peshmerga - from the Ottoman Empire to Present-Day Iraq (page 63)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029191132/http://etd.lib.fsu.edu/theses/available/etd-11142005-144616/unrestricted/003Manuscript.pdf |date=29 October 2013 }}, Michael G. Lortz</ref><br />\n{{flagicon|Iraq|1991}} Iraq: 30,000 (1996)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.countriesquest.com/middle_east/iraq/history/persian_gulf_war_and_aftermath.htm |title=Persian Gulf War and Aftermath - History - Iraq - Middle East: embargo iraq, crisis iraq, power united, exchange rate, end year |publisher=Countriesquest.com |date=15 January 1991 |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref><br />\n{{flag|Turkey}}: 50,000 (1997)<ref name=\"KDP\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gP_-8rXzQs8C&pg=PA4227|title=The Europa World Year: Kazakhstan - Zimbabwe|publisher=|accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag of KDP-I.png}} PDKI: 600 (1998)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,74703,00.html|title=Iraqi Insurgent Groups|work=Fox News|accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n|strength2={{flagicon image|Flag of PUK.png}} PUK: 12,000 active, 6,000 reserves<ref name=\"fsu\"/><br />INC: 1,000 (1995)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historycommons.org/timeline.jsp?specific_cases_and_issues=chalabi&timeline=complete_timeline_of_the_2003_invasion_of_iraq|title=Events Leading Up to the 2003 Invasion of Iraq|publisher=|accessdate=1 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116052701/http://www.historycommons.org/timeline.jsp?specific_cases_and_issues=chalabi&timeline=complete_timeline_of_the_2003_invasion_of_iraq|archive-date=16 November 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag of Kurdistan Workers' Party 1978.svg}} PKK: 5,000\u201310,000 (1994)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/war/kurdistan-turkey-insurrection.htm|title=Kurdistan - Turkey|author=John Pike|publisher=|accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><br />\n{{flag|Iran}}: 2,000 (1996)<ref>[http://www.irainc.org/pub/NIreport.pdf Unsafe Haven: Iranian Kurdish Refugees in Iraqi Kurdistan (page 1)]</ref><br />\n{{flagicon image|Badr Organisation Military flag.svg}} [[SCIRI]]: 5,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meforum.org/384/turkey-and-iran-face-off-in-kurdistan |title=Turkey and Iran Face off in Kurdistan :: Middle East Quarterly |publisher=Meforum.org |date= |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref>\n|casualties1=\n|casualties2=\n|casualties3=5,000 killed<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Middle_East/LB20Ak02.html |title=Asia Times Online :: Middle East News, Iraq, Iran current affairs |publisher=Atimes.com |date=20 February 2010 |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Iraqi Kurdish Civil War}}\n{{Campaignbox Kurdish\u2013Iraqi conflict}}\n{{Campaignbox Kurdish\u2013Turkish conflict}}\n\nThe '''Iraqi Kurdish Civil War''' was a military conflict that took place between rival [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]] factions in [[Iraqi Kurdistan]] during the mid-1990s, mostly between the [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]] and the [[Kurdistan Democratic Party]]. Over the course of the conflict, Kurdish factions from [[Iranian Kurdistan|Iranian]] and [[Turkish Kurdistan]], as well as Iranian, Iraqi and Turkish state forces, were drawn into the fighting, with additional involvement from American forces. Between 3,000 and 5,000 fighters and civilians were killed.\n\n==Background==\nAutonomy in [[Iraqi Kurdistan]] was originally established in 1970 as the ''Kurdish Autonomous Region'' following the agreement of an Autonomy Accord between the government of Iraq and leaders of the Iraqi [[Kurds|Kurdish]] community. A Legislative Assembly was established in the city of Erbil with nominal authority over the Kurdish-populated governorates of [[Erbil Governorate|Erbil]], [[Dohuk Governorate|Dahuk]] and [[As Sulaymaniyah Governorate|As Sulaymaniyah]]. As various battles between separatist Kurds and Iraqi government forces continued until the [[1991 uprisings in Iraq]], the safety of Kurdish refugees led to the adoption of [[United Nations Security Council]] [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 688|Resolution 688]] which was used as a justification to implement [[Operation Provide Comfort]], a US-led multinational military operation that ensured the security of the Iraqi Kurdish region through the use of air power while simultaneously providing humanitarian aid to refugees fleeing persecution.<ref>L. Fawcett, ''Down but not out? The Kurds in International Politics'', Reviews of International Studies, Vol.27, 2001 p.117</ref> While the no-fly zone covered Dahuk and Erbil, it left out Sulaymaniyah and [[Kirkuk]]. This led to a further series of bloody clashes between Iraqi government forces and Kurdish troops. Shortly thereafter, an uneasy balance of power was reached, and Iraq withdrew its military and government officials from the region in October 1991. From that point on, Iraqi Kurdistan had achieved ''de facto'' independence under the leadership of the region's two principal Kurdish parties \u2013 the [[Kurdistan Democratic Party of Iraq|Kurdish Democratic Party]] and the [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]] \u2013 free from the control of [[Baghdad]]. The region then adopted its own flag and national anthem.\n\nIraqi Kurdistan held [[1992 Iraqi Kurdistan parliamentary election|parliamentary elections]] in 1992. The KDP gained an absolute majority of the votes in the [[Governorates of Iraq|governorates]] of [[Dohuk Governorate|Dohuk]] and [[Arbil Province|Arbil]], whereas the PUK garnered the broad support of the [[Sulaymaniyah Governorate|Sulaymaniyah]] governorate as well as the Kurdish portions of [[Diyala Governorate|Diyala]] (specifically the [[Kifri District|Kifri]] and [[Khanaqin District]]s). As a result of the election, the Kurdish parliament was split between [[Jalal Talabani]]'s Patriotic Union of Kurdistan and [[Massoud Barzani]]'s Kurdish Democratic Party.<ref name=\"slate.com\">{{cite web|last=Politi |first=Daniel |url=http://www.slate.com/id/1032/ |title=The Kurds - Slate Magazine |publisher=Slate.com |date= |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter withdrawing its forces from Kurdistan in October 1991, the Iraqi government imposed an economic blockade over the region, restricting its oil and food supplies.<ref>M. Leezenberg, ''Iraqi Kurdistan: contours of a post-civil war society'', Third World Quarterly, Vol.26, No.4-5, June 2005, p.636</ref> The United Nations embargo on Iraq also significantly affected the Kurdish economy, preventing trade between the Kurds and other nations. As such, all economic dealings between Iraqi Kurdistan and the outside world were done through the [[black market]].\n\nIn March 1994 [[Turkish Armed Forces]] began [[Operation Steel]], a cross-border military incursion into [[Iraqi Kurdistan|northern Iraq]] against the [[Kurdistan Workers' Party|PKK]]. On May 3 a delegation from the KDP agreed to not allow the PKK to have a base in northern Iraq. On May 4, Turkish Armed Forces left northern Iraq.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kurds in Turkey |url=http://www.asylumlaw.org/docs/turkey/mar99_turkey_kurds.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716081035/http://www.asylumlaw.org/docs/turkey/mar99_turkey_kurds.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=16 July 2011 |website=Asylum Law |accessdate=19 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==1994 PUK\u2013KDP clashes==\n{{main|May 1994 PUK\u2013KDP clashes}}\n\nFighting broke out between the two factions in May 1994. The initial clashes left around 300 people dead, <ref name=\"globalsecurity.org\">{{cite web|author=John Pike |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/kdp.htm |title=Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) |publisher=Globalsecurity.org |date= |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref> and over the next year, around 2,000 people were killed on both sides.<ref name=\"slate.com\"/> According to former CIA officer [[Robert Baer]], members of the Iranian [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] provided limited support to the PUK and allowed the PUK to launch attacks from Iranian territory.\n\n==Planned assassination of Saddam Hussein==\nIn January 1995, [[CIA]] case officer [[Robert Baer]] traveled to northern Iraq with a five-man team to set up a CIA station. He made contact with the Kurdish leadership and managed to negotiate a truce between Barzani and Talabani.\n\nWithin days, Baer made contact with an Iraqi general who was plotting to assassinate [[Saddam Hussein]]. The plan was to use a unit of 100 renegade Iraqi troops to kill Saddam as he passed over a bridge near [[Tikrit]]. Baer cabled the plan to Washington but did not hear anything back. After three weeks, the plan was revised, calling for an attack by Kurdish forces in northern Iraq while rebel Iraqi troops leveled one of Saddam's houses with tank fire in order to kill the Iraqi leader. Baer again cabled the plan to Washington and received no response. On 28 February, the [[Iraqi Army]] was placed on full alert. In response, the Iranian and Turkish militaries were also placed on high alert. Baer received a message directly from National Security Advisor [[Tony Lake]] telling him his operation was compromised. This warning was passed on Baer's Kurdish and Iraqi contacts. Upon learning this, Barzani backed out of the planned offensive, leaving Talabani's PUK forces to carry it out alone.\n\nThe Iraqi Army officers planning to kill Saddam with tank fire were compromised, arrested and executed before they could carry out the operation. The PUK's offensive was still launched as planned, and within days they managed to destroy three Iraqi Army divisions and capture 5,000 prisoners.<ref name=\"wmassociation.com\">[http://www.wmassociation.com/reports/spkers/baer.html Robert Baer speech at World Media Association]  {{webarchive |url=https://archive.today/20070816094817/http://www.wmassociation.com/reports/spkers/baer.html |date=16 August 2007 }}</ref> Despite Baer's pleas for American support of the offensive, none was forthcoming, and the Kurdish troops were forced to withdraw. Baer was immediately recalled from Iraq, briefly investigated for the attempted murder of Saddam Hussein, but exonerated.<ref name=\"wmassociation.com\"/>\n\n==Battle of Erbil (1996)==\n{{main|Battle of Erbil (1996)}}\nAlthough the Kurdish parliament ceased to meet in May 1996, the fragile cease-fire between the PUK and KDP held until the summer of 1996. During this period, the Iraqi government was permitted by the KDP to establish a smuggling route through the [[Khabur (Euphrates)|Khabur River]] basin for the transportation of illegal petroleum exports.<ref name=\"TTS1\">{{cite book|last1=Pollack|first1=Kenneth|title=The Threatening Storm: What Every American Needs to Know Before an Invasion in Iraq|date=25 March 2003|publisher=Random House LLC, 2003|isbn=9781588363411|page=81|edition=The Case for Invading Iraq: An Excerpt from The Threatening Storm|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HCZfUV-U97kC&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&source=bl&ots=6vPivVVOt_&sig=hX-9bcgfdd2M-aiaCt2IjW0HmxU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=WR2qU9L2L4OYyASTyILgDA&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=25 June 2014}}</ref> Barzani and his associates seized the opportunity to impose taxation on this trade, giving them an income of several million dollars per week.<ref>{{cite book |last=Stansfield |first=G. |last2=Anderson |first2=L. |title=The Future of Iraq: Dictatorship, Democracy, or Division? |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |location=New York |year=2004 |page=174 |isbn=1403963541}}</ref> This led to a dispute with the PUK over who should benefit from this money. Although the two parties reached an agreement where the Iraqi\u2013Turkish smuggling routes would be divided evenly between them, the KDP continued its attempts to exert greater control over the movement of goods through Iraqi Kurdistan.<ref name=TTS1 />\n\nTalabani established an alliance with Iran, permitting it to conduct a military incursion into northern Iraq aimed at the [[Kurdish Democratic Party of Iran]] on 28 July.<ref name=\"slate.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=John Pike |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/kdpi.htm |title=Kurdish Democratic Party of Iran (KDPI) |publisher=Globalsecurity.org |date= |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref> In response, Barzani asked for assistance from the Iraqi government who, seeing an opportunity to retake northern Iraq, accepted. On 31 August, 30,000 Iraqi troops, spearheaded by an armored division of the [[Iraqi Republican Guard]], attacked the PUK-held city of [[Erbil]], which was defended by 3,000 PUK Peshmerga led by Korsat Rasul Ali, in conjunction with KDP forces. Erbil was captured, and Iraqi troops executed 700 PUK and [[Iraqi National Congress]] [[prisoners of war]] in a field outside the city.\n\nThis attack stoked Kurdish fears that Saddam intended to launch a genocidal campaign against the Kurds similar to the campaigns of [[Al-Anfal Campaign|1988]] and [[1991 uprisings in Iraq|1991]]. The Clinton administration, unwilling to allow the Iraqi government to regain control of Iraqi Kurdistan, began [[Operation Desert Strike]] on 3 September, when American ships and [[B-52 Stratofortress]] bombers launched 27 cruise missiles at air defense sites in southern Iraq. The next day, 17 more cruise missiles were launched from American ships against Iraqi air defense sites. The United States also deployed strike aircraft and an aircraft carrier to the [[Persian Gulf]] region, and the extent of the southern no-fly zone was moved northwards to the [[33rd parallel north|33rd parallel]].<ref>{{cite web|author=John Pike |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/ops/desert_strike.htm |title=Operation Desert Strike |publisher=Globalsecurity.org |date= |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter installing the KDP in control of Erbil, [[Iraqi Army]] troops withdrew from the Kurdish region back to their initial positions. The KDP drove the PUK from its other strongholds, and with additional Iraqi Army help, captured Sulaymaniyah on 9 September. Jalal Talabani and the PUK retreated to the Iranian border, and American forces evacuated 700 Iraqi National Congress personnel and 6,000 PUK members out of northern Iraq.<ref name=\"slate.com\"/><ref name=\"globalsecurity.org\"/> On 13 October, Sulaymaniyah was recaptured by the PUK, allegedly with support of Iranian forces.<ref name=\"UNHCR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/country,,MARP,,IRQ,,469f38a6c,0.html|title=Refworld - Chronology for Kurds in Iraq|author=United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|work=Refworld|accessdate=1 May 2016|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017070825/http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/country%2C%2CMARP%2C%2CIRQ%2C%2C469f38a6c%2C0.html|archivedate=17 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Turkish intervention==\n{{main|Operation Hammer (1997)|Operation Dawn (1997)}}\n\nFighting continued throughout the winter between the KDP and PUK. Complicating matters, PKK was present in Iraq. PKK was allied with the PUK which later led KDP attack the PKK. According to some sources, the PKK began to fight against all who supported KDP, including some Assyrian and Arab groups.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|author=John Pike |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/puk.htm |title=Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) |publisher=Globalsecurity.org |date= |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref> Turkey which saw the Kurdish Civil war as an opportunity, allied with KDP and launched [[Operation Hammer (1997)|Operation Hammer]] in May, in a violent attempt to force the PKK to leave Iraqi Kurdistan. This operation caused heavy PKK casualties but was unsuccessful. PKK succeeded to keep their camps in Northern Iraq.<ref>{{cite book|title=The State of the Middle East: An Atlas of Conflict and Resolution|page=92|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MehRAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA92&lpg=PA92&dq=KDP+attacked+PKK+1994&source=bl&ots=4LYoA6JpQH&sig=jfnfDJT2P7NXlpZck0ZvXK0b_58&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjYiIWqrpfLAhXDJJoKHbJXDy4Q6AEIKzAE#v=onepage&q=KDP%20attacked%20PKK%201994&f=false|accessdate=27 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September 1997, Turkish forces re-entered Iraqi Kurdistan and attacked PUK and PKK positions in an attempt to force the PKK to leave Iraqi Kurdistan. However, according to Turkish sources, it was an attempt to bring a cease-fire between the factions. The operation resulted in heavy PKK and PUK casualties. Later a cease-fire was negotiated between the PUK and KDP after the US decision to support a cease-fire.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nDespite the cease-fire, renewed fighting broke out along the armistice line between the KDP and PUK in October and November. In this round of fighting, 1,200 combatants were killed on both sides and 10,000 civilians fled their homes.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> On 24 November 1997, the KDP declared a unilateral cease-fire. The PUK, although not declaring a cease-fire officially, said their group would respect the truce, despite alleging that the KDP had violated the truce by attacking PUK positions on 25 November.<ref name=\"UNHCR\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Iraq kurdish areas 2003 vector.svg|300px|thumb|Division of Kurdistan after the civil war]]\n\nIn September 1998, [[Massoud Barzani|Barzani]] and [[Jalal Talabani|Talabani]] signed the U.S.-mediated Washington Agreement establishing a formal peace treaty. In the agreement, the parties agreed to share revenue, share power, deny the use of northern Iraq to the [[Kurdistan Workers' Party|PKK]], and not allow Iraqi troops into the Kurdish regions. The United States pledged to use military force to protect the Kurds from possible aggression by [[Saddam Hussein]]. At the same time, implementation of the U.N. [[Oil-for-Food Programme]] brought revenue to northern Iraq, allowing for increased standards of living.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewashingtoninstitute.org/templateC05.php?CID=1219 |title=Kurdish Agreement Signals New U.S. Commitment |publisher=The Washington Institute for Near East Policy |date=29 September 1998 |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref> Iraqi Kurdistan became a relatively peaceful region, before the small terrorist group [[Ansar al-Islam]] entered the Halabja region in December 2001, bringing renewed conflict that would end in 2003 immediately prior to start of Iraq war, which mainly affected non-Kurdish areas of Iraq.\n\nAround a month later, U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]] signed the [[Iraq Liberation Act]] into law, providing for military assistance to Iraqi opposition groups, including the PUK and KDP. The KDP estimated that 58,000 of its supporters had been expelled from PUK-controlled regions from October 1996 to October 1997. The PUK says 49,000 of its supporters were expelled from KDP-controlled regions from August 1996 to December 1997.<ref name=\"globalsecurity.org\" />\n\nThe PUK and KDP later co-operated with American forces during the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], routing Iraqi forces with the help of American air power and overrunning much of northern Iraq including the cities of [[Kirkuk]] and [[Mosul]]. After the invasion, Massoud Barzani was later elected president of Iraqi Kurdistan while Jalal Talabani was elected [[President of Iraq]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of wars involving Iraq]]\n* [[List of wars involving Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n* [[List of modern conflicts in the Middle East]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* [https://www.jstor.org/stable/pdf/4328927.pdf?seq=1 The KDP-PUK Conflict in Northern Iraq]\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Cite book|isbn=140004684X|title=See No Evil: The True Story of a Ground Soldier in the CIA's War on Terrorism |last=Baer |first=Robert |publisher=Three Rivers Press|year=2003}}\n* {{Cite book|isbn=0375509283|title=The Threatening Storm: The Case for Invading Iraq|last=Pollack|first=Kenneth|publisher=Random House|year=2002|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/threateningstorm00poll}}\n\n{{Post-Cold War Asian conflicts}}\n\n[[Category:Iraqi\u2013Kurdish conflict]]\n[[Category:1994 in Iraq]]\n[[Category:1995 in Iraq]]\n[[Category:1996 in Iraq]]\n[[Category:1997 in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1994]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1995]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1996]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1997]]\n[[Category:Civil wars in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Civil wars post-1945]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Iran]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Iraq]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Kurdistan Region (Iraq)]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the United States]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Turkey]]\n[[Category:1990s in Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n", "name_user": "130.193.249.166", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iraqi_Kurdish_Civil_War"}
{"title_page": "Charli D'Amelio", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Short description|American social media personality}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Charli D'Amelio\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|2004|5|1}}\n| birth_place        = [[Norwalk, Connecticut]], U.S.<ref name=\"norwalk\">{{Cite web|url=https://dailyvoice.com/connecticut/norwalk/lifestyle/norwalk-15-year-old-dancer-surges-to-stardom-on-social-media-with-five-million-followers/779708/|title=Norwalk 15-Year-Old Dancer Surges To Stardom On Social Media With Five Million Followers|date=November 25, 2019 website=Norwalk Daily Voice|language=en|access-date=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| occupation         = {{hlist|[[Social media personality]]|Dancer}}\n| years_active       = 2019\u2013present\n| known_for          = [[TikTok]]\n}}\n\n'''Charli D'Amelio''' (born May 1, 2004)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/celebs/amp31019692/who-is-charli-damelio-tiktok/|title=TikTok Star Charli D\u2019Amelio Has No Idea How She Got So Famous|work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> is an American [[social media personality]] and dancer. As of April 2020, she has accumulated over 50.0 million followers on the social video sharing app  [[TikTok]], and has been called the \"reigning queen of TikTok\" by the ''[[New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/03/style/hype-house-los-angeles-tik-tok.html |title=Hype House and the Los Angeles TikTok Mansion Gold Rush |last=Lorenz |first=Taylor |date=January 3, 2020 |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=January 25, 2020}} </ref> She is the [[List of most-followed TikTok accounts|most-followed]] individual on the platform.\n\n==Career==\nD'Amelio's career began on [[TikTok]] in the summer of 2019 with uploaded dance videos. She has since acquired over 50.0 million [[TikTok]] followers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tiktok.com/@charlidamelio?isUniqueId=true&sec_uid=|title=charli d\u2019amelio on TikTok|website=TikTok|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> 15.2 million [[Instagram]] followers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/charlidamelio/|title=charli d\u2019amelio (@charlidamelio) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos|website=www.instagram.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> 2.58 million [[YouTube]] subscribers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCi3OE-aN09WOcN9d2stCvPg|title=charli d'amelio|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> and over 846 thousand [[Twitter]] followers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/charlidamelio|title=charli d\u2019amelio (@charlidamelio) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> In just 10 months, she became the [[List of most-followed TikTok accounts|most-followed account]] on the social media platform [[TikTok]]. She surpassed the previous most-followed individual, [[Loren Gray]], on March 25, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_most-followed_TikTok_accounts|title=List of most-followed TikTok accounts - Wikipedia|website=en.m.wikipedia.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, D'Amelio signed with talent agency [[United Talent Agency|UTA]].<ref name=\"times\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/hollywood-agency-uta-signs-tiktoks-teen-star-charli-damelio-qchbk3v6c |title=Hollywood agency UTA signs TikTok\u2019s teen star Charli D\u2019Amelio |last=Fortson |first=Danny |date=January 19, 2020 |website=[[The Sunday Times]] |access-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref> She then landed a spot in a Super Bowl commercial for Sabra Hummus along with other celebrities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/2/21119668/tiktok-super-bowl-ad-charli-damelio-hyundai-mountain-dew-justin-bieber|title=TikTok has its Super Bowl moment in more ways than one|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=2020-02-02|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref> She was invited to attend Super Bowl LIV and meet [[Jennifer Lopez]] to create the viral [[TikTok]] challenge \"J Lo Super Bowl Challenge.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/tiktok-star-charli-damelio-on-her-dream-come-true-dance-with-jennifer-lopez-exclusive-140744|title=TikTok Star Charli D'Amelio on Her Dance With Jennifer Lopez|website=Entertainment Tonight|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\nShe is a part of the collaborative [[TikTok]] web group \"[[The Hype House|Hype House]]\" along with 18 others including [[Addison Rae Easterling]] and Dixie D'Amelio.<ref name=\"nyt\" /><ref name=\"insi\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.insider.com/hype-house-members-charli-d-amelio-lilhuddy-tiktok-los-angeles-2020-1|title=TikTok's Hype House is home to some of the app's biggest stars, including Charli D'Amelio. Who are the other 20 members?|last=Perrett|first=Connor|website=Insider|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\nShe has been invited to perform at the NBA All-Star game, performing with fellow Hype House members Addison Rae, her sister Dixie, and creator of the \"renegade\" dance, Jalaiah Harmon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insider.com/renegade-creator-danced-charli-damelio-nba-all-star-game-2020-2|title=The original 'Renegade' dance creator Jalaiah Harmon collaborated with Charli D'Amelio and performed at the NBA All-Star Game|last=Harris|first=Margot|website=Insider|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref> On March 27, 2020, D'Amelio collaborated on [[YouTube]] with actor [[Noah Schnapp]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=NL9Oub28wUU&feature=youtu.be|title=Noah Schnapp Teaches Me How To Act! {{!}} Charli D\u2019Amelio|last=D\u2019Amelio|first=Charli|date=March 27, 2020|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHer immediate family includes politician and father, Marc D'Amelio, her mother, Heidi D'Amelio, and her sister, Dixie D'Amelio.<ref name=\"nbcnews\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/pop-culture/viral/meet-charli-d-amelio-tiktok-s-newest-viral-teen-celebrity-n1092626 |title=Meet Charli D'Amelio, TikTok's newest viral teen celebrity |last=Rosenblatt |first=Kalhan |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=November 28, 2019 |access-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nD'Amelio has been subject to bullying and body shaming.<ref name=body/> She and her sister, Dixie, have partnered with [[UNICEF]], speaking out against online bullying and the perils of finding fame on the platform.<ref name=body>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insider.com/charli-dixie-damelio-tik-tok-biggest-stars-cyberbullying-video-2020-2|title=One of TikTok's biggest stars say she gets hundreds of thousands of hate comments every week, often focusing on her body and weight|last=Lustig|first=Hanna|website=Insider|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{TikTok}}\n* {{Instagram}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Damelio, Charli}}\n[[Category:2004 births]]\n[[Category:American TikTokers]]\n[[Category:Female TikTokers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American dancers]]\n[[Category:American children]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Norwalk, Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Short description|American social media personality}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Charli D'Amelio\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|2004|5|1}}\n| birth_place        = [[Norwalk, Connecticut]], U.S.<ref name=\"norwalk\">{{Cite web|url=https://dailyvoice.com/connecticut/norwalk/lifestyle/norwalk-15-year-old-dancer-surges-to-stardom-on-social-media-with-five-million-followers/779708/|title=Norwalk 15-Year-Old Dancer Surges To Stardom On Social Medi