{"title_page": "Mubashir Hassan", "text_new": "{{short description|Pakistani engineer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = \n| office              = Entrepreneur and youngest self made millionaire of Pakistan\n| mainwidth           = \n| preceded            = \n| president           = \n| primeminister       = \n| succeeding          = \n| successor           = \n| termend             = \n| termstart           = \n| office1             = Founder of a successful Tech companies in Pakistan and abroad.\n| predecessor1        = \n| president1          = \n| primeminister1      = \n| successor1          = \n| termend1            = \n| termstart1          = \n| termstart2          = \n| birth_date          = 17 August 1996\n| birth_place         = Khyber Pakhton Khwa\n| death_date          = Alive\n| nationality         = [[Pakistani]]\n| alma_mater          = Bahria University Karachi\n| occupation          = Entrepreneur\n}}\n\n'''Mubashir Hassan''' ({{lang-ur|{{nq|\u0645\u0628\u0634\u0631 \u062d\u0633\u0646}}}}; 22 January 1922 \u2013 14 March 2020) was a Pakistan politician and [[Finance Minister of Pakistan|Finance Minister]] of the Bhutto government.\n\nIn 1967, Hassan co-founded the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]], a [[Democratic socialism|democratic socialist]] political force, with [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] and J.A. Rahim.<ref name=\"National Books (United States)\"/> In 1972, Hassan helped Bhutto establish the [[Ministry of Science and Technology (Pakistan)|Ministry of Science]], where he financially assisted large number of Pakistan's academic scientists in the application of Science in warfare.<ref name=\"Printwise Publications\"/> During the 1970s, Hassan emerged as effective public policy maker and was the Prime minister's [[Ministry of Science and Technology (Pakistan)#Science Advisors|science adviser]]. However, after [[Operation Fair Play|removal]] of Prime minister Bhutto, Hassan became troubled, and was successfully silenced by the [[Zia regime|military government]] of [[General Zia-ul-Haq]].<ref name=\"National Books (United States)\"/>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Panipat]], [[Punjab]], now [[Haryana]], Hassan attended the [[Punjab University, Lahore|Punjab University]] in 1947 prior to [[Creation of Pakistan|establishment]] of Pakistan, gaining BSc in civil engineering.<ref name=\"Chowk.com\">{{Cite web\n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | authorlink =\n  | author2 =\n  | title =Dr. Mubashir Hassan\n  | website =\n  | publisher =Chowk.com\n  | date =\n  | url =http://www.chowk.com/pavocavalry/iLogs/life/DR-Mubashir-Hassan\n  | format =\n  | doi =\n  | accessdate =\n  }}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In the 1950s, Hassan travelled to [[United States]] where he gained [[MSc]] in civil engineering from [[Iowa State University]], and finally gaining doctorate in civil engineering after submitting his doctoral thesis on fundamental problems and their solution on [[Hydraulic engineering]].<ref name=\"Chowk.com\"/>\n\nAfter returning to [[West Pakistan|West-Pakistan]], Hassan joined the [[University of Engineering and Technology, Lahore|University of Engineering and Technology]] at [[Lahore]] teaching courses on civil engineering which remained his lifelong passion. His political philosophy began to take place in 1967, after witnessing the [[Indo-Pakistani war of 1965|1965 war]] with India. In 1967, Hassan published the political manifesto, \"A Declaration of Unity of People\", advocating for [[Technocracy|Techno-]] [[Democratic socialism]] in [[East Pakistan|East-Pakistan]], during which he was lecturing in the topic of [[Engineering physics]] at the [[University of Dhaka|Dhaka University]].\n\n===Political activism===\nAfter gaining appreciation and popularity, [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] called Hassan to [[West Pakistan|West-Pakistan]] where at his house, the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] was founded along with [[Jalaludin Abdur Rahim|J.A. Rahim]].<ref name=\"Chowk.com\"/><ref>{{Cite web\n  | last =Pakistan Herald\n  | authorlink =\n  | title =Intellectual: Dr. Mubashir Hassan\n  | website =\n  | publisher =Pakistan Herald\n  | date =\n  | url = http://pakistanherald.com/Profile/Dr-Mubashir-Hassan-1067\n  | format =\n  | doi =\n  | accessdate = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web\n| title =Delegation visits with Dr. Mubashir Hasan\n| url =http://vcnv.org/gallery2/main.php/v/pakistan-+delegation/Dan+Pearson/pakistan-delegation/Dr_+Mubashir+Hasan.jpg.html\n| accessdate =\n| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20130624094004/http://vcnv.org/gallery2/main.php/v/pakistan-+delegation/Dan+Pearson/pakistan-delegation/Dr_+Mubashir+Hasan.jpg.html\n| archive-date =24 June 2013\n| url-status =dead\n}}</ref> His wide knowledge in ranging from science and politics, Hassan became one of the closest confidants and advisers of Bhutto, and acted on behalf of Bhutto in 1970 to form a coalition government with [[Shaikh Mujibur Rahman|Mujibur Rahman]] of [[Awami League|Peoples League]].<ref name=\"Lokyan and Rainbow Publishing Limited\">{{cite book|last=Zia Mian|first=Smitu Kothari|title=Out of the Nuclear Shadow\u00a7 Condemning the Nuclear war|publisher=Lokyan and Rainbow Publishing Limited|location=New Delhi; Islamabad|isbn=8186962263|pages=416\u2013490|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YSSNtPs521cC&pg=PA418 |year=2001}}</ref>  After the [[Indo-Pakistani war of 1971|1971 Winter war]], Hassan was appointed [[Finance Minister of Pakistan|Finance Minister]] and helped Bhutto establish the [[Ministry of Science and Technology (Pakistan)|Ministry of Science]] in 1[[972]].<ref name=\"Printwise Publications\"/>\n\n===Atomic bomb project===\nHis political role in [[Pakistan and weapons of mass destruction|atomic bomb project]] started in 1972, when Bhutto asked him to meet with [[Munir Ahmad Khan]] of [[Pakistan Atomic Energy Commission]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}} Bhutto responded by abolishing several committees dealing with atomic energy in various [[Cabinet of Pakistan|ministries]], and ordered [[Finance Minister]]Hassan to manage the finance of the atomic bomb project.{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}}Meanwhile, Hassan reportedly worked closely with [[Munir Ahmad Khan]] on technical and economical aspects of the atomic bomb project.{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}} He remained supportive and administrative figure in [[Pakistan]]'s [[Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty|non-nuclear proliferation]], and monitored [[Abdul Qadeer Khan]]'s suspicious activities throughout 1976.<ref name=\"Lokyan and Rainbow Publishing Limited\"/> However, he was soon pulled out after being warned by Bhutto, therefore, Hassan focused his attention on PAEC's efforts.<ref name=\"Lokyan and Rainbow Publishing Limited\"/>\n\nIn 1974, he developed serious issues with Bhutto after Bhutto deposed [[Malik Meraj Khalid]], a Marxist and [[Law Minister of Pakistan|Law Minister]] when Bhutto decided to expand the activities of the [[The Establishment|establishment]] in the government to keep an eye on [[Pakistan National Alliance|Bhutto rivals]].<ref name=\"National Books (United States)\">{{cite book|last=Bhutto|first=Fatima|title=Songs of Blood and Sword: A Daughter's Memoir|year=2010|publisher=National Books (United States)|location=Washington D.C. United States|isbn=978-1-56858-632-8|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781568586328/page/116 116]\u2013130|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781568586328|url-access=registration|quote=dr mubashir hasan finance minister.}}</ref>  In 1974, Hassan resigned from [[Finance Ministry]] after learning of this incident, but remained loyal to Bhutto.<ref name=\"National Books (United States)\"/> In 1974, Bhutto finally appointed Hassan as his [[Ministry of Science and Technology (Pakistan)|Science Advisor to the Prime minister Secretariat]].<ref name=\"National Books (United States)\"/> As Director of Directorate for Science, Hassan played a significant role in the establishment of [[Kahuta Project]], advising Bhutto on various aspects of atomic bomb project.<ref name=\"Printwise Publications\">{{cite book|last=Rahman|first=Shahidur|title=Long Road to Chagai: \u00a7A Man hurry for the Bomb|year=1999|publisher=Printwise Publications|location=Islamabad|isbn=969-8500-00-6|pages=157|ol=155472M}}</ref> He objected to the idea of giving the Kahuta Project's responsibilities to [[Pakistan Army Corps of Engineers|Corps of Engineers]], but was overruled by Bhutto.<ref name=\"Printwise Publications\"/> However, the progress on atomic bomb project was slowed down after an intensified civil disorder began to take place, shrinking the credibility of Bhutto.<ref name=\"Printwise Publications\"/> Throughout 1976, Hassan made several unsuccessful attempts to bring the leadership of [[Pakistan National Alliance]] on table and he was finally arrested by [[Military Police]] in 1977.<ref name=\"Printwise Publications\"/> Hassan was placed in [[Adiala Jail]] with Bhutto where he spent his next seven years in prison even after Bhutto's execution.<ref name=\"Printwise Publications\"/>\n\n===Post war activities===\nReleased in 1984, Hassan joined the [[UET Lahore]]'s [[Faculty (division)|Faculty]] of [[Engineering]] as [[professor]] of civil engineering.<ref name=\"Chowk.com\"/> In 1988, Prime minister [[Benazir Bhutto]] made an attempt to appoint him as [[Finance Minister]] but was denied after Benazir had planned [[deregulation]] of industries.<ref name=\"Chowk.com\"/> Although, Hassan had retired from any political activism, Hassan continued to write articles in hydraulics engineering and its extended mathematical problems.<ref name=\"Chowk.com\"/> Hassan also wrote about the economic issues and remained a loyal supporter of [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] and his policies.<ref>{{cite web|last=Articles written by dr. Hassan Muabshir|title=Reducing the trust deficit|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/TodaysPrintWriterName.aspx?URL=Dr%20Mubashir%20Hasan|publisher=The News International|accessdate=19 December 2011}}</ref> His articles were regularly published in ''[[The News International]]'', though he was associated with the [[Pakistan Peoples Party (Shaheed Bhutto)|Pakistan Peoples Party (Murtaza Bhutto)]] since its inception.<ref name=\"The News International, Islamabad\">{{cite news|last=Our Correspondent|title=True advocate of PPP ideology|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/TodaysPrintWriterName.aspx?URL=Dr%20Mubashir%20Hasan|accessdate=19 December 2011|newspaper=The News International, Islamabad|date=24 October 2011}}</ref> In 2011, Hassan visited his native city in [[India]], where Hassan advocated normalisation of [[Indo-Pakistani relations|Indo-Pakistan relations]], and maintained that:\n\n{{quote|text=Since 1974, [[Pakistan]] had enormously helped the people of [[Afghanistan]] in expelling the [[Soviet Union]].... Judging by present situation, if the [United States]-[Afghanistan] axis were to invade Pakistan, [[India]] would stand by [[Pakistan]] and not with the invaders|sign=Hassan Mubasir|source=<ref name=\"The News International, Islamabad\"/>}}\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Books and bibliography===\n*2001, ''Birds of the Indus'', Mubashir Hasan, Tom J. Roberts\n*2000, ''The Mirage of Power'', Dr. Mubashir Hassan, PhD, (2000) ({{ISBN|0-19-579300-5}})\n*1989, ''An Enquiry into the Bhutto Years'', Dr. Mubashir Hassan\n*1986, ''National unity: what is to be done?'', Mubashir Hasan, I. A. Rahman, A. H. Kardar\n*1977, ''United front for people's democracy''\n*1976, ''Pakistan's illiterate leaders''\n*1967, ''A Declaration of Unity of People''\n*1954, ''On the general education of an engineer''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef | before =[[Abdus Salam]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Ministry of Science and Technology (Pakistan)#Science Advisors|Science Advisor to the Prime minister Secretariat]] | years = 22 October 1974 \u2013 5 July 1977}}\n{{s-aft | after =[[Major-General|MGen]] [[Zahid Ali Akbar|Zahid A. Akbar]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[Nawab Muzaffar Ali Khan Qizilbash|Muzaffar Ali Khan Qizilbash]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Finance Minister of Pakistan|Finance Minister]] of Pakistan | years = 24 December 1971 \u2013 22 October 1974}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Rana Mohammad Hanif Khan|RM Hanif Khan]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Finance Minister of Pakistan}}\n{{Government of Prime minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hassan, Mubashir}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Pakistani civil engineers]]\n[[Category:University of Engineering and Technology, Lahore faculty]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Peoples Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Project-706 people]]\n[[Category:Government of Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]]\n[[Category:Finance Ministers of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Pakistani academics]]\n[[Category:Pakistani educators]]\n[[Category:Pakistani socialists]]\n[[Category:Technocracy movement]]\n[[Category:Iowa State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of the Punjab alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia School of Engineering and Applied Science alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Panipat]]\n[[Category:Pakistani people of Haryanvi descent]]\n[[Category:Pakistani dissidents]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pakistani engineer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = \n| office              = 10th [[Finance, Revenue and Economic Affairs Minister of Pakistan|Minister of Finance, Planning & Development]]\n| mainwidth           = \n| preceded            = [[Muzaffar Ali Khan Qizilbash]]\n| president           = \n| primeminister       = [[Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto]]\n| succeeding          = \n| successor           = [[Rana Mohammad Hanif Khan]]\n| termend             = 22 October 1974\n| termstart           = 24 December 1971\n| office1             = [[Ministry of Science and Technology (Pakistan)|Science Advisor to the Prime Minister of Pakistan]]\n| predecessor1        = [[Abdul Salam]]\n| president1          = \n| primeminister1      = [[Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto]]\n| successor1          = [[Zahid Ali Akbar Khan]]\n| termend1            = 5 July 1977\n| termstart1          = 22 October 1974\n| termstart2          = \n| birth_date          = 17 August 1996\n| birth_place         = Khyber Pakhton Khwa\n| death_date          = Alive\n| nationality         = [[Pakistani]]\n| alma_mater          = <nowiki>[[University of the Punjab|Punjab </nowiki>\n| occupation          = Entrepreneur\n}}\n\n'''Mubashir Hassan''' ({{lang-ur|{{nq|\u0645\u0628\u0634\u0631 \u062d\u0633\u0646}}}}; 22 January 1922 \u2013 14 March 2020) was a Pakistan politician and [[Finance Minister of Pakistan|Finance Minister]] of the Bhutto government.\n\nIn 1967, Hassan co-founded the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]], a [[Democratic socialism|democratic socialist]] political force, with [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] and J.A. Rahim.<ref name=\"National Books (United States)\"/> In 1972, Hassan helped Bhutto establish the [[Ministry of Science and Technology (Pakistan)|Ministry of Science]], where he financially assisted large number of Pakistan's academic scientists in the application of Science in warfare.<ref name=\"Printwise Publications\"/> During the 1970s, Hassan emerged as effective public policy maker and was the Prime minister's [[Ministry of Science and Technology (Pakistan)#Science Advisors|science adviser]]. However, after [[Operation Fair Play|removal]] of Prime minister Bhutto, Hassan became troubled, and was successfully silenced by the [[Zia regime|military government]] of [[General Zia-ul-Haq]].<ref name=\"National Books (United States)\"/>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Panipat]], [[Punjab]], now [[Haryana]], Hassan attended the [[Punjab University, Lahore|Punjab University]] in 1947 prior to [[Creation of Pakistan|establishment]] of Pakistan, gaining BSc in civil engineering.<ref name=\"Chowk.com\">{{Cite web\n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | authorlink =\n  | author2 =\n  | title =Dr. Mubashir Hassan\n  | website =\n  | publisher =Chowk.com\n  | date =\n  | url =http://www.chowk.com/pavocavalry/iLogs/life/DR-Mubashir-Hassan\n  | format =\n  | doi =\n  | accessdate =\n  }}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In the 1950s, Hassan travelled to [[United States]] where he gained [[MSc]] in civil engineering from [[Iowa State University]], and finally gaining doctorate in civil engineering after submitting his doctoral thesis on fundamental problems and their solution on [[Hydraulic engineering]].<ref name=\"Chowk.com\"/>\n\nAfter returning to [[West Pakistan|West-Pakistan]], Hassan joined the [[University of Engineering and Technology, Lahore|University of Engineering and Technology]] at [[Lahore]] teaching courses on civil engineering which remained his lifelong passion. His political philosophy began to take place in 1967, after witnessing the [[Indo-Pakistani war of 1965|1965 war]] with India. In 1967, Hassan published the political manifesto, \"A Declaration of Unity of People\", advocating for [[Technocracy|Techno-]] [[Democratic socialism]] in [[East Pakistan|East-Pakistan]], during which he was lecturing in the topic of [[Engineering physics]] at the [[University of Dhaka|Dhaka University]].\n\n===Political activism===\nAfter gaining appreciation and popularity, [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] called Hassan to [[West Pakistan|West-Pakistan]] where at his house, the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] was founded along with [[Jalaludin Abdur Rahim|J.A. Rahim]].<ref name=\"Chowk.com\"/><ref>{{Cite web\n  | last =Pakistan Herald\n  | authorlink =\n  | title =Intellectual: Dr. Mubashir Hassan\n  | website =\n  | publisher =Pakistan Herald\n  | date =\n  | url = http://pakistanherald.com/Profile/Dr-Mubashir-Hassan-1067\n  | format =\n  | doi =\n  | accessdate = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web\n| title =Delegation visits with Dr. Mubashir Hasan\n| url =http://vcnv.org/gallery2/main.php/v/pakistan-+delegation/Dan+Pearson/pakistan-delegation/Dr_+Mubashir+Hasan.jpg.html\n| accessdate =\n| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20130624094004/http://vcnv.org/gallery2/main.php/v/pakistan-+delegation/Dan+Pearson/pakistan-delegation/Dr_+Mubashir+Hasan.jpg.html\n| archive-date =24 June 2013\n| url-status =dead\n}}</ref> His wide knowledge in ranging from science and politics, Hassan became one of the closest confidants and advisers of Bhutto, and acted on behalf of Bhutto in 1970 to form a coalition government with [[Shaikh Mujibur Rahman|Mujibur Rahman]] of [[Awami League|Peoples League]].<ref name=\"Lokyan and Rainbow Publishing Limited\">{{cite book|last=Zia Mian|first=Smitu Kothari|title=Out of the Nuclear Shadow\u00a7 Condemning the Nuclear war|publisher=Lokyan and Rainbow Publishing Limited|location=New Delhi; Islamabad|isbn=8186962263|pages=416\u2013490|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YSSNtPs521cC&pg=PA418 |year=2001}}</ref>  After the [[Indo-Pakistani war of 1971|1971 Winter war]], Hassan was appointed [[Finance Minister of Pakistan|Finance Minister]] and helped Bhutto establish the [[Ministry of Science and Technology (Pakistan)|Ministry of Science]] in 1[[972]].<ref name=\"Printwise Publications\"/>\n\n===Atomic bomb project===\nHis political role in [[Pakistan and weapons of mass destruction|atomic bomb project]] started in 1972, when Bhutto asked him to meet with [[Munir Ahmad Khan]] of [[Pakistan Atomic Energy Commission]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}} Bhutto responded by abolishing several committees dealing with atomic energy in various [[Cabinet of Pakistan|ministries]], and ordered [[Finance Minister]]Hassan to manage the finance of the atomic bomb project.{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}}Meanwhile, Hassan reportedly worked closely with [[Munir Ahmad Khan]] on technical and economical aspects of the atomic bomb project.{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}} He remained supportive and administrative figure in [[Pakistan]]'s [[Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty|non-nuclear proliferation]], and monitored [[Abdul Qadeer Khan]]'s suspicious activities throughout 1976.<ref name=\"Lokyan and Rainbow Publishing Limited\"/> However, he was soon pulled out after being warned by Bhutto, therefore, Hassan focused his attention on PAEC's efforts.<ref name=\"Lokyan and Rainbow Publishing Limited\"/>\n\nIn 1974, he developed serious issues with Bhutto after Bhutto deposed [[Malik Meraj Khalid]], a Marxist and [[Law Minister of Pakistan|Law Minister]] when Bhutto decided to expand the activities of the [[The Establishment|establishment]] in the government to keep an eye on [[Pakistan National Alliance|Bhutto rivals]].<ref name=\"National Books (United States)\">{{cite book|last=Bhutto|first=Fatima|title=Songs of Blood and Sword: A Daughter's Memoir|year=2010|publisher=National Books (United States)|location=Washington D.C. United States|isbn=978-1-56858-632-8|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781568586328/page/116 116]\u2013130|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781568586328|url-access=registration|quote=dr mubashir hasan finance minister.}}</ref>  In 1974, Hassan resigned from [[Finance Ministry]] after learning of this incident, but remained loyal to Bhutto.<ref name=\"National Books (United States)\"/> In 1974, Bhutto finally appointed Hassan as his [[Ministry of Science and Technology (Pakistan)|Science Advisor to the Prime minister Secretariat]].<ref name=\"National Books (United States)\"/> As Director of Directorate for Science, Hassan played a significant role in the establishment of [[Kahuta Project]], advising Bhutto on various aspects of atomic bomb project.<ref name=\"Printwise Publications\">{{cite book|last=Rahman|first=Shahidur|title=Long Road to Chagai: \u00a7A Man hurry for the Bomb|year=1999|publisher=Printwise Publications|location=Islamabad|isbn=969-8500-00-6|pages=157|ol=155472M}}</ref> He objected to the idea of giving the Kahuta Project's responsibilities to [[Pakistan Army Corps of Engineers|Corps of Engineers]], but was overruled by Bhutto.<ref name=\"Printwise Publications\"/> However, the progress on atomic bomb project was slowed down after an intensified civil disorder began to take place, shrinking the credibility of Bhutto.<ref name=\"Printwise Publications\"/> Throughout 1976, Hassan made several unsuccessful attempts to bring the leadership of [[Pakistan National Alliance]] on table and he was finally arrested by [[Military Police]] in 1977.<ref name=\"Printwise Publications\"/> Hassan was placed in [[Adiala Jail]] with Bhutto where he spent his next seven years in prison even after Bhutto's execution.<ref name=\"Printwise Publications\"/>\n\n===Post war activities===\nReleased in 1984, Hassan joined the [[UET Lahore]]'s [[Faculty (division)|Faculty]] of [[Engineering]] as [[professor]] of civil engineering.<ref name=\"Chowk.com\"/> In 1988, Prime minister [[Benazir Bhutto]] made an attempt to appoint him as [[Finance Minister]] but was denied after Benazir had planned [[deregulation]] of industries.<ref name=\"Chowk.com\"/> Although, Hassan had retired from any political activism, Hassan continued to write articles in hydraulics engineering and its extended mathematical problems.<ref name=\"Chowk.com\"/> Hassan also wrote about the economic issues and remained a loyal supporter of [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] and his policies.<ref>{{cite web|last=Articles written by dr. Hassan Muabshir|title=Reducing the trust deficit|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/TodaysPrintWriterName.aspx?URL=Dr%20Mubashir%20Hasan|publisher=The News International|accessdate=19 December 2011}}</ref> His articles were regularly published in ''[[The News International]]'', though he was associated with the [[Pakistan Peoples Party (Shaheed Bhutto)|Pakistan Peoples Party (Murtaza Bhutto)]] since its inception.<ref name=\"The News International, Islamabad\">{{cite news|last=Our Correspondent|title=True advocate of PPP ideology|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/TodaysPrintWriterName.aspx?URL=Dr%20Mubashir%20Hasan|accessdate=19 December 2011|newspaper=The News International, Islamabad|date=24 October 2011}}</ref> In 2011, Hassan visited his native city in [[India]], where Hassan advocated normalisation of [[Indo-Pakistani relations|Indo-Pakistan relations]], and maintained that:\n\n{{quote|text=Since 1974, [[Pakistan]] had enormously helped the people of [[Afghanistan]] in expelling the [[Soviet Union]].... Judging by present situation, if the [United States]-[Afghanistan] axis were to invade Pakistan, [[India]] would stand by [[Pakistan]] and not with the invaders|sign=Hassan Mubasir|source=<ref name=\"The News International, Islamabad\"/>}}\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Books and bibliography===\n*2001, ''Birds of the Indus'', Mubashir Hasan, Tom J. Roberts\n*2000, ''The Mirage of Power'', Dr. Mubashir Hassan, PhD, (2000) ({{ISBN|0-19-579300-5}})\n*1989, ''An Enquiry into the Bhutto Years'', Dr. Mubashir Hassan\n*1986, ''National unity: what is to be done?'', Mubashir Hasan, I. A. Rahman, A. H. Kardar\n*1977, ''United front for people's democracy''\n*1976, ''Pakistan's illiterate leaders''\n*1967, ''A Declaration of Unity of People''\n*1954, ''On the general education of an engineer''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef | before =[[Abdus Salam]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Ministry of Science and Technology (Pakistan)#Science Advisors|Science Advisor to the Prime minister Secretariat]] | years = 22 October 1974 \u2013 5 July 1977}}\n{{s-aft | after =[[Major-General|MGen]] [[Zahid Ali Akbar|Zahid A. Akbar]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[Nawab Muzaffar Ali Khan Qizilbash|Muzaffar Ali Khan Qizilbash]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Finance Minister of Pakistan|Finance Minister]] of Pakistan | years = 24 December 1971 \u2013 22 October 1974}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Rana Mohammad Hanif Khan|RM Hanif Khan]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Finance Minister of Pakistan}}\n{{Government of Prime minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto