{"title_page": "Unit of volume", "text_new": "[[File:Pompeji 6 Hohlma\u00dfe aus Glas.jpg|thumb|6&nbsp;volumetric measures from the ''mens ponderia'' in [[Pompeii]], a municipal institution for the control of weights and measures (79&nbsp;A.&nbsp;D.)]]\nA '''unit of volume''' is a [[unit of measurement]] for measuring [[volume]] or capacity, the extent of an object or space in three [[dimension (mathematics)|dimensions]]. Units of capacity may be used to specify the volume of fluids or bulk goods, for example water, rice, sugar, grain or flour. \nyou could use different units.\n\n== Units ==\nAccording to the [[International System of Units|SI system]], the [[base unit (measurement)|base unit]] for measuring length is the [[metre]] and volumes are thus measured in [[cubic metre]]s, where:\n\n1 m<sup>3</sup> = 1 m \u2022 1 m \u2022 1 m.\n\n== Comparison ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Volume\n! Unit of measure                     !! [[cubic metre]]      !! [[litre]]       !! Reference size                       || Usage     \n|- class=\"hintergrundfarbe 9\"\n| 1 [[cubic metre]]               || = 1                 || = 1000         ||                                      || [[base unit (measurement)|base unit]] in SI\n|-\n| 1 [[barrel (unit)|barrel]]                   || = 0.158 987 294 928 || = 158.987294928 || = 42 US gallons = 9,702 cubic inches || e.&nbsp;g. for [[mineral oil|oil]]\n|-\n| 1 [[cubic foot]]      || = 0.028 316 846 592 || = 28.316864592  || = 1,728 cubic inches                    ||\n|- class=\"hintergrundfarbe 9\"\n| 1 [[cubic decimetre]]           || = 0.001             || = 1             ||                                      ||\n|-\n| 1 [[litre]]                    || = 0.001             || = 1             ||                                      ||\n|-\n| 1 [[gallon]] (US)             || = 0.003 785 411 784 || = 3.785411784   || = 8 pints (US) = 231 cubic inches       ||\n|-\n| 1 [[pint]] (US)                || = 0.000 473 176 473 || = 0.473176473   ||                                      ||\n|-\n| 1 [[cubic inch]]     || = 0.000 016 387 064 || = 0.016387064   ||                                      ||\n|- class=\"hintergrundfarbe 9\"\n| 1 [[cubic centimetre]]          || = 0.000 001         || = 0.0010000     ||                                      ||\n|}\n\n== Forestry and timber industry ==\n\n=== British Commonwealth ===\n* [[Hoppus]], cubic foot measure used in the British Empire and, nowadays, some Commonwealth countries for timber.\n\n=== Germany ===\n* [[Festmeter]] (fm), a unit of volume for logs\n** Erntefestmeter (Efm), a unit of volume for trees or forests which assumes a 10% loss due to bark and 10% during the felling process.\n** Vorratsfestmeter (Vfm), a unit of volume for trees or forests based on measurements including the bark.\n* [[Raummeter]] (rm), or [[stere]] (stacked [[firewood]]) = 0.7&nbsp;m<sup>3</sup> (stacked woodpile with air spaces)\n** Sch\u00fcttmeter, or Sch\u00fcttraummeter (piled wood with air spaces)\n\n=== USA and Canada ===\n* [[Board foot]], unit of lumber\n* [[Cord (unit)|Cord]], a unit of dry volume used to measure firewood and [[pulpwood]]\n* [[Cubic yard]], equal to {{val|27|u=cuft}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Faggot (unit)|Faggot]]\n* [[History of measurement]]\n* [[Orders of magnitude (volume)]]\n* [[Metre Convention]]\n* [[Physical quantity]]\n* [[Tonne (unit)]]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n{{Wiktionary|Hohlma\u00df|Volume units}}\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Units of volume| ]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Pompeji 6 Hohlma\u00dfe aus Glas.jpg|thumb|6&nbsp;volumetric measures from the ''mens ponderia'' in [[Pompeii]], a municipal institution for the control of weights and measures (79&nbsp;A.&nbsp;D.)]]\nA '''unit of volume''' is a [[unit of measurement]] for measuring [[volume]] or capacity, the extent of an object or space in three [[dimension (mathematics)|dimensions]]. Units of capacity may be used to specify the volume of fluids or bulk goods, for example water, rice, sugar, grain or flour.\n\n== Units ==\nAccording to the [[International System of Units|SI system]], the [[base unit (measurement)|base unit]] for measuring length is the [[metre]] and volumes are thus measured in [[cubic metre]]s, where:\n\n1 m<sup>3</sup> = 1 m \u2022 1 m \u2022 1 m.\n\n== Comparison ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Volume\n! Unit of measure                     !! [[cubic metre]]      !! [[litre]]       !! Reference size                       || Usage     \n|- class=\"hintergrundfarbe 9\"\n| 1 [[cubic metre]]               || = 1                 || = 1000         ||                                      || [[base unit (measurement)|base unit]] in SI\n|-\n| 1 [[barrel (unit)|barrel]]                   || = 0.158 987 294 928 || = 158.987294928 || = 42 US gallons = 9,702 cubic inches || e.&nbsp;g. for [[mineral oil|oil]]\n|-\n| 1 [[cubic foot]]      || = 0.028 316 846 592 || = 28.316864592  || = 1,728 cubic inches                    ||\n|- class=\"hintergrundfarbe 9\"\n| 1 [[cubic decimetre]]           || = 0.001             || = 1             ||                                      ||\n|-\n| 1 [[litre]]                    || = 0.001             || = 1             ||                                      ||\n|-\n| 1 [[gallon]] (US)             || = 0.003 785 411 784 || = 3.785411784   || = 8 pints (US) = 231 cubic inches       ||\n|-\n| 1 [[pint]] (US)                || = 0.000 473 176 473 || = 0.473176473   ||                                      ||\n|-\n| 1 [[cubic inch]]     || = 0.000 016 387 064 || = 0.016387064   ||                                      ||\n|- class=\"hintergrundfarbe 9\"\n| 1 [[cubic centimetre]]          || = 0.000 001         || = 0.0010000     ||                                      ||\n|}\n\n== Forestry and timber industry ==\n\n=== British Commonwealth ===\n* [[Hoppus]], cubic foot measure used in the British Empire and, nowadays, some Commonwealth countries for timber.\n\n=== Germany ===\n* [[Festmeter]] (fm), a unit of volume for logs\n** Erntefestmeter (Efm), a unit of volume for trees or forests which assumes a 10% loss due to bark and 10% during the felling process.\n** Vorratsfestmeter (Vfm), a unit of volume for trees or forests based on measurements including the bark.\n* [[Raummeter]] (rm), or [[stere]] (stacked [[firewood]]) = 0.7&nbsp;m<sup>3</sup> (stacked woodpile with air spaces)\n** Sch\u00fcttmeter, or Sch\u00fcttraummeter (piled wood with air spaces)\n\n=== USA and Canada ===\n* [[Board foot]], unit of lumber\n* [[Cord (unit)|Cord]], a unit of dry volume used to measure firewood and [[pulpwood]]\n* [[Cubic yard]], equal to {{val|27|u=cuft}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Faggot (unit)|Faggot]]\n* [[History of measurement]]\n* [[Orders of magnitude (volume)]]\n* [[Metre Convention]]\n* [[Physical quantity]]\n* [[Tonne (unit)]]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n{{Wiktionary|Hohlma\u00df|Volume units}}\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Units of volume| ]]\n", "name_user": "92.11.95.115", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_of_volume"}
{"title_page": "Maurice Wetherill", "text_new": "{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = Maurice Wetherill\n|fullname       = Maurice Charles Wetherill\n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        =  \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|SO|HB}}\n|birth_date    = \n|birth_place = Auckland, New Zealand\n|death_date = 1983\n|height         =  5 ft 10 in\n|weight         =  10 st 7 lb\n|club1          = [[City Rovers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|ARL]]\n|year1start     = 1920\n|year1end       = 25\n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 24\n|goals1         = 16\n|fieldgoals1    = 0\n|points1        = 104 \n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1921\n|yearAend       = 25\n|appearancesA   = 24\n|triesA         = 8\n|goalsA         = 3\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 30\n|teamB               = Auckland Province\n|yearBstart          =1922\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 1\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         =0 \n|pointsB             = 3\n|teamC              = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearCstart          =1924 \n|yearCend            =  30\n|appearancesC        = 20\n|triesC              = \n|goalsC              = \n|fieldgoalsC         = \n|pointsC             = \n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nMaurice Wetherill was a New Zealand rugby league player. He represented New Zealand from 1924 to 1930 and was Kiwi number 156. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = NZRL \u2013 Past Kiwis\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url = https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===Early Life===\nMaurice Wetherill was born in [[Auckland]] on January 15, 1928. He was the son of Maurice Charles Wetherill and Mary Ann Wetherill. He had a brother, James Ewart Wetherill, and sister Ivy Pearl Wetherill. He was a plumber by trade and at the time of signing up for [[World War 1]] he was living on Ardmore Road in [[Ponsonby, New Zealand|Ponsonby]] with his family and working for A.J. Letham. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Wetherill, Maurice Charles \u2013 WW1 History Sheet\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Auckland Museum\n| url = https://ndhadeliver.natlib.govt.nz/delivery/DeliveryManagerServlet?dps_pid=IE20834584\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===World War 1===\nMaurice Wetherill enlisted in the armed forces on February 27, 1918 aged 20. At the time of his service his weight was recorded as 122lb, and his height 5 feet 5 inches. He commenced duty on March 14, 1918 and embarked for [[Suez]], [[Egypt]] on the ''Moeraki'' on October 11. The ship stopped in [[Sydney]] where the soldiers 'transhipped' to the Malta to complete the journey.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Cenotaph Record \u2013 Maurice Charles Wetherill\n| publisher = Auckland Museum\n| url = https://ndhadeliver.natlib.govt.nz/delivery/DeliveryManagerServlet?dps_pid=IE20834584\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Wetherill was part of the Mounted Rifles \u2013 43rd reinforcements. When he signed up for World War 1 he recorded his address as Ardmore Road in Ponsonby where he was living with his family. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Cenotaph Records\n| publisher = Auckland Museum\n| url = https://media.api.aucklandmuseum.com/id/media/v/322529?rendering=original.jpg\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> He served in Egypt during the latter part of the war and when his overseas duty was complete he departed [[Plymouth]], [[England]] for New Zealand on board the ''Hororata''. Wetherill was discharged from duty on October 18, 1919 after 1 year and 219 days duty, and 346 days served overseas. He later received the [[British War Medal]] for his service.\n\n===Playing career===\nAfter returning from the war Wetherill joined the [[City Rovers]] rugby league club where he played for the senior team in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He was small in stature, measuring just 5 feet 5 inches and spent his career playing in the halves or on the wing. In his first season for City he scored 4 tries and kicked 4 conversions including a try on debut.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Opening of the Season/City\u2019s Big Win\n| page =7\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LI| issue=105\n| date = 1920-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19200503.2.63\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref> In [[1921 Auckland Rugby League season|1921]] the City team won the Monteith Shield by winning the first grade championship. They also won the Roope Rooster trophy after defeating Maritime in the final by 30 points to 14 with Wetherill kicking a conversion.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Final/Victory For City Team/Fast and Exciting Game\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17902\n| date = 1921-10-03\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19211003.2.114.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-26}}</ref> He made his [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] debut this same season and went on to play 7 matches for them. His first match in an Auckland jersey was against the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] team at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 11,000 spectators. Auckland lost the match 22-16.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand V Auckland/Local Team Defeated\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]\n| date = 1921-05-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210523.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref> He then played against [[Wellington rugby league team|Wellington]] for the [[Rugby League Cup|Northern Union Challenge Cup]] which Auckland won 31-8. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Wellington/Victory For Local Team/Game Played In Rain\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17848\n| date = 1921-08-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210801.2.107.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref> Wetherill then played 5 further matches all resulting in wins, against Hawkes Bay ((18-3), [[Wellington rugby league team|Wellington]] (23-21), West Coast (47-7), Canterbury (38-14), and [[Waikato rugby league team|South Auckland]] (35-13).<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland Beats Hawke\u2019s Bay/Fast Game On Wet Ground\n| page =3\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXIII| issue=17854\n| date = 1921-08-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210808.2.18\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Wellington/Margin Of Two Points\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17866\n| date = 1921-08-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210822.2.92.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V West Coast/An Easy Victory\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17869\n| date = 1921-09-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210825.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Canterbury/Win For Northerners/Thirty-Nine To Fourteen\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17872\n| date = 1921-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210829.2.93.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V South Auckland/Victory For Local Team/Fast Spectacular Play\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17890\n| date = 1921-09-19\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210919.2.105.2\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1922 Auckland Rugby League season|1922]] Wetherill scored 8 tries during the season for [[City Rovers|City]] as they again won the first grade championship. Remarkably Wetherill played in 9 matches for Auckland. He scored a try in the 18-28 loss to [[New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby league team|New Zealand M\u0101ori]]. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Maori\u2019s Play Well/Defeat of Auckland/28 Points to Eighteen/Fast and Exciting Game/Visitors Show Great Dash\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18096\n| date = 1922-05-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220522.2.121\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref> He then played 3 matches against the touring Australian University side scoring a try in the 3rd match. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Australian University V Auckland/Visitors Win By a Point\n| page =8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIII| issue=146\n| date = 1922-06-22\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19220622.2.105\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Universities V Auckland/Australians\u2019 Second Win/Good Game at Domain\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18126\n| date = 1922-06-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220626.2.105\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Universities V Auckland/Australians\u2019 Second Win/Good Game at Domain\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18126\n| date = 1922-06-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220626.2.105\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref> Wetherill turned out again for Auckland in a [[Rugby League Cup|Northern Union Challenge Cup]] match against Hawkes Bay with Auckland retaining the trophy and Wetherill touching down for another try in a 23-5 win.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay/Win For the Local Team\n| page =5\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18174\n| date = 1922-08-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220821.2.29\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref> Prior to this he has been part of the 73-29 thrashing of [[Cambridge, New Zealand|Cambridge]] where he crossed the line once. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Cambridge/Won by 73 Points to 29\n| page = 4\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18153\n| date = 1922-07-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220727.2.7.1\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref> He then went on to play in a loss to [[Waikato rugby league team|South Auckland]] which saw the [[Rugby League Cup|Northern Union Challenge Cup]] change hands. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Challenge Cup/Win by South Auckland/Fast and Exciting Game/Twenty-One Points to Twenty\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18186\n| date = 1922-09-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220904.2.122\n| accessdate = 2019-08-29}}</ref> Wetherill was to represent Auckland against the touring [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] side where they were well beaten 25-40 with Wetherill kicking a conversion, and he played the same team 4 days later but playing for Auckland Province this time in a 20-21 defeat.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =New South Wales Team\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18198\n| date = 1922-09-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220918.2.111\n| accessdate = 2019-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =League \"Rep\" Match/New South Wales Team/Game Against Province/Win by 21 Points to 20\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18201\n| date = 1922-09-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220921.2.109\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref> His final representative match of the season was an Auckland effort to regain the Northern Union Challenge Cup from South Auckland which was unsuccessful. South Auckland win the match 26-18 and retained the trophy for the summer. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =South Auckland Win/Fast and Open League Play/Auckland Thirteen Defeated/28-16 At the Close\n| page = 6\n| work = Waikato Times| volume=96| issue=15056\n| date = 1922-10-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/WT19221002.2.66\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1923 Auckland Rugby League season|1923]] he was part of the [[City Rovers]] team which won the first grade championship for the 3rd consecutive season. He played 2 matches for Auckland. The first was against the Auckland Province side which saw the city team win 44-15 with Wetherill scoring a try.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Beats Province/In Match of Big Scoring\n| page =9\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIV| issue=234\n| date = 1923-10-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19231001.2.134\n| accessdate = 2019-09-02}}</ref> While the second match was against South Auckland at [[Carlaw Park]] and on this occasion Wetherill scored twice in a 35-11 win. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Close of the Season/Auckland 35; S. Auckland 11\n| page =10\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LX| issue=18530\n| date = 1923-10-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19231015.2.170.1\n| accessdate = 2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\nWetherill played 5 matches for Auckland in 1924 and he also made his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut. He played at halfback in the first test against the touring [[England rugby league team|England]] side and scored New Zealand\u2019s first try in the corner in a 16-8 win. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = First League Test/Win for New Zealand\n| page = 10\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LV, Issue 183\n| date = 1924-08-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19240804.2.142\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Unfortunately Wetherill was unable to travel south to play in the remaining test matches which saw New Zealand lose twice and therefore lose the series 1-2.\n\nThe [[1925 Auckland Rugby League season|1925]] season saw Wetherill selected for the New Zealand team to tour [[Australia]]. His weight was listed as 10 stone, 7 pounds which was a significant increase on his weight when he had signed up for the war 5 years earlier. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Fifteen Aucklanders\n| page = 11\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 152\n| date = 1925-06-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250630.2.107\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Wetherill played a remarkable 10 matches on the tour of Australia and a further 2 matches for New Zealand against [[Queensland rugby league team|Queensland]] when they toured New Zealand later in the year. While he missed many matches for [[City Rovers]] while on tour he still helped to captain the side to another first grade championship where they edged out [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]].\n\nHe played all 3 test matches for New Zealand against the touring England team in 1928. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = New Zealand vs England 1928\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/new-zealand-vs-england-1928/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Wetherill also toured Australia again in 1930, playing 4 more matches for New Zealand. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Tour 1930\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kiwis-tour-1930/squad.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===Personal Life and Death===\nMaurice Wetherill was married on October 19, 1923 to Stella Jessen. They had one son, Maurice George Wetherill. His son passed away in 1970 aged 47. Maurice\u2019s father who was also named Maurice Charles Wetherill died in 1925 aged 56, his mother Mary died in 1932 aged 55, while his wife Stella died in 1964 aged 60.\n\nMaurice Wetherill died in 1983 aged 85.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wetherill, Maurice}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:City Rovers players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = Maurice Wetherill\n|fullname       = Maurice Charles Wetherill\n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        =  \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|SO|HB}}\n|birth_date    = \n|birth_place = Auckland, New Zealand\n|death_date = 1983\n|height         =  5 ft 10 in\n|weight         =  10 st 7 lb\n|club1          = [[City Rovers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|ARL]]\n|year1start     = 1920\n|year1end       = 25\n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 24\n|goals1         = 16\n|fieldgoals1    = 0\n|points1        = 104 \n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1921\n|yearAend       = 25\n|appearancesA   = 24\n|triesA         = 8\n|goalsA         = 3\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 30\n|teamB               = Auckland Province\n|yearBstart          =1922\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 1\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         =0 \n|pointsB             = 3\n|teamC              = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearCstart          =1924 \n|yearCend            =  30\n|appearancesC        = 20\n|triesC              = \n|goalsC              = \n|fieldgoalsC         = \n|pointsC             = \n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nMaurice Wetherill was a New Zealand rugby league player. He represented New Zealand from 1924 to 1930 and was Kiwi number 156. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = NZRL \u2013 Past Kiwis\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url = https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===Early Life===\nMaurice Wetherill was born in [[Auckland]] on January 15, 1928. He was the son of Maurice Charles Wetherill and Mary Ann Wetherill. He had a brother, James Ewart Wetherill, and sister Ivy Pearl Wetherill. He was a plumber by trade and at the time of signing up for [[World War 1]] he was living on Ardmore Road in [[Ponsonby, New Zealand|Ponsonby]] with his family and working for A.J. Letham. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Wetherill, Maurice Charles \u2013 WW1 History Sheet\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Auckland Museum\n| url = https://ndhadeliver.natlib.govt.nz/delivery/DeliveryManagerServlet?dps_pid=IE20834584\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===World War 1===\nMaurice Wetherill enlisted in the armed forces on February 27, 1918 aged 20. At the time of his service his weight was recorded as 122lb, and his height 5 feet 5 inches. He commenced duty on March 14, 1918 and embarked for [[Suez]], [[Egypt]] on the ''Moeraki'' on October 11. The ship stopped in [[Sydney]] where the soldiers 'transhipped' to the Malta to complete the journey.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Cenotaph Record \u2013 Maurice Charles Wetherill\n| publisher = Auckland Museum\n| url = https://ndhadeliver.natlib.govt.nz/delivery/DeliveryManagerServlet?dps_pid=IE20834584\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Wetherill was part of the Mounted Rifles \u2013 43rd reinforcements. When he signed up for World War 1 he recorded his address as Ardmore Road in Ponsonby where he was living with his family. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Cenotaph Records\n| publisher = Auckland Museum\n| url = https://media.api.aucklandmuseum.com/id/media/v/322529?rendering=original.jpg\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> He served in Egypt during the latter part of the war and when his overseas duty was complete he departed [[Plymouth]], [[England]] for New Zealand on board the ''Hororata''. Wetherill was discharged from duty on October 18, 1919 after 1 year and 219 days duty, and 346 days served overseas. He later received the [[British War Medal]] for his service.\n\n===Playing career===\nAfter returning from the war Wetherill joined the [[City Rovers]] rugby league club where he played for the senior team in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He was small in stature, measuring just 5 feet 5 inches and spent his career playing in the halves or on the wing. In his first season for City he scored 4 tries and kicked 4 conversions including a try on debut.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Opening of the Season/City\u2019s Big Win\n| page =7\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LI| issue=105\n| date = 1920-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19200503.2.63\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref> In [[1921 Auckland Rugby League season|1921]] the City team won the Monteith Shield by winning the first grade championship. They also won the Roope Rooster trophy after defeating Maritime in the final by 30 points to 14 with Wetherill kicking a conversion.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Final/Victory For City Team/Fast and Exciting Game\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17902\n| date = 1921-10-03\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19211003.2.114.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-26}}</ref> He made his [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] debut this same season and went on to play 7 matches for them. His first match in an Auckland jersey was against the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] team at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 11,000 spectators. Auckland lost the match 22-16.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand V Auckland/Local Team Defeated\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]\n| date = 1921-05-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210523.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref> He then played against [[Wellington rugby league team|Wellington]] for the [[Rugby League Cup|Northern Union Challenge Cup]] which Auckland won 31-8. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Wellington/Victory For Local Team/Game Played In Rain\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17848\n| date = 1921-08-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210801.2.107.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref> Wetherill then played 5 further matches all resulting in wins, against Hawkes Bay ((18-3), [[Wellington rugby league team|Wellington]] (23-21) , West Coast (47-7), Canterbury (38-14), and [[Waikato rugby league team|South Auckland]] (35-13).<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland Beats Hawke\u2019s Bay/Fast Game On Wet Ground\n| page =3\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXIII| issue=17854\n| date = 1921-08-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210808.2.18\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Wellington/Margin Of Two Points\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17866\n| date = 1921-08-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210822.2.92.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V West Coast/An Easy Victory\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17869\n| date = 1921-09-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210825.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Canterbury/Win For Northerners/Thirty-Nine To Fourteen\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17872\n| date = 1921-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210829.2.93.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V South Auckland/Victory For Local Team/Fast Spectacular Play\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17890\n| date = 1921-09-19\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210919.2.105.2\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1922 Auckland Rugby League season|1922]] Wetherill scored 8 tries during the season for [[City Rovers|City]] as they again won the first grade championship. Remarkably Wetherill played in 9 matches for Auckland. He scored a try in the 18-28 loss to [[New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby league team|New Zealand M\u0101ori]]. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Maori\u2019s Play Well/Defeat of Auckland/28 Points to Eighteen/Fast and Exciting Game/Visitors Show Great Dash\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18096\n| date = 1922-05-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220522.2.121\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref> He then played 3 matches against the touring Australian University side scoring a try in the 3rd match. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Australian University V Auckland/Visitors Win By a Point\n| page =8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIII| issue=146\n| date = 1922-06-22\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19220622.2.105\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Universities V Auckland/Australians\u2019 Second Win/Good Game at Domain\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18126\n| date = 1922-06-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220626.2.105\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Universities V Auckland/Australians\u2019 Second Win/Good Game at Domain\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18126\n| date = 1922-06-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220626.2.105\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref> Wetherill turned out again for Auckland in a [[Rugby League Cup|Northern Union Challenge Cup]] match against Hawkes Bay with Auckland retaining the trophy and Wetherill touching down for another try in a 23-5 win.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay/Win For the Local Team\n| page =5\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18174\n| date = 1922-08-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220821.2.29\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref> Prior to this he has been part of the 73-29 thrashing of [[Cambridge, New Zealand|Cambridge]] where he crossed the line once. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Cambridge/Won by 73 Points to 29\n| page = 4\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18153\n| date = 1922-07-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220727.2.7.1\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref> He then went on to play in a loss to [[Waikato rugby league team|South Auckland]] which saw the [[Rugby League Cup|Northern Union Challenge Cup]] change hands. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Challenge Cup/Win by South Auckland/Fast and Exciting Game/Twenty-One Points to Twenty\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18186\n| date = 1922-09-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220904.2.122\n| accessdate = 2019-08-29}}</ref> Wetherill was to represent Auckland against the touring [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] side where they were well beaten 25-40 with Wetherill kicking a conversion, and he played the same team 4 days later but playing for Auckland Province this time in a 20-21 defeat.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =New South Wales Team\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18198\n| date = 1922-09-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220918.2.111\n| accessdate = 2019-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =League \"Rep\" Match/New South Wales Team/Game Against Province/Win by 21 Points to 20\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18201\n| date = 1922-09-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220921.2.109\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref> His final representative match of the season was an Auckland effort to regain the Northern Union Challenge Cup from South Auckland which was unsuccessful. South Auckland win the match 26-18 and retained the trophy for the summer. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =South Auckland Win/Fast and Open League Play/Auckland Thirteen Defeated/28-16 At the Close\n| page = 6\n| work = Waikato Times| volume=96| issue=15056\n| date = 1922-10-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/WT19221002.2.66\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1923 Auckland Rugby League season|1923]] he was part of the [[City Rovers]] team which won the first grade championship for the 3rd consecutive season. He played 2 matches for Auckland. The first was against the Auckland Province side which saw the city team win 44-15 with Wetherill scoring a try.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Beats Province/In Match of Big Scoring\n| page =9\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIV| issue=234\n| date = 1923-10-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19231001.2.134\n| accessdate = 2019-09-02}}</ref> While the second match was against South Auckland at [[Carlaw Park]] and on this occasion Wetherill scored twice in a 35-11 win. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Close of the Season/Auckland 35; S. Auckland 11\n| page =10\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LX| issue=18530\n| date = 1923-10-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19231015.2.170.1\n| accessdate = 2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\nWetherill played 5 matches for Auckland in 1924 and he also made his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut. He played at halfback in the first test against the touring [[England rugby league team|England]] side and scored New Zealand\u2019s first try in the corner in a 16-8 win. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = First League Test/Win for New Zealand\n| page = 10\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LV, Issue 183\n| date = 1924-08-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19240804.2.142\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Unfortunately Wetherill was unable to travel south to play in the remaining test matches which saw New Zealand lose twice and therefore lose the series 1-2.\n\nThe [[1925 Auckland Rugby League season|1925]] season saw Wetherill selected for the New Zealand team to tour [[Australia]]. His weight was listed as 10 stone, 7 pounds which was a significant increase on his weight when he had signed up for the war 5 years earlier. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Fifteen Aucklanders\n| page = 11\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 152\n| date = 1925-06-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250630.2.107\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Wetherill played a remarkable 10 matches on the tour of Australia and a further 2 matches for New Zealand against [[Queensland rugby league team|Queensland]] when they toured New Zealand later in the year. While he missed many matches for [[City Rovers]] while on tour he still helped to captain the side to another first grade championship where they edged out [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]].\n\nHe played all 3 test matches for New Zealand against the touring England team in 1928. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = New Zealand vs England 1928\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/new-zealand-vs-england-1928/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Wetherill also toured Australia again in 1930, playing 4 more matches for New Zealand. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Tour 1930\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kiwis-tour-1930/squad.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===Personal Life and Death===\nMaurice Wetherill was married on October 19, 1923 to Stella Jessen. They had one son, Maurice George Wetherill. His son passed away in 1970 aged 47. Maurice\u2019s father who was also named Maurice Charles Wetherill died in 1925 aged 56, his mother Mary died in 1932 aged 55, while his wife Stella died in 1964 aged 60.\n\nMaurice Wetherill died in 1983 aged 85.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wetherill, Maurice}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:City Rovers players]]\n", "name_user": "Llunnaz", "label": "safe", "comment": "punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maurice_Wetherill"}
